A Republican strategy to oppose Obama's reelection
The Republican leadership justifies its policies by the need to combat electoral fraud.
However, the Brennan Center considers the latter a myth, affirming that voter fraud in the United States is less common than the number of people killed by lightning.
By the way, Republican lawyers have only recorded 300 cases of voter fraud in the United States in 10 years.
One thing is certain: these new rules will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, these measures are partly undermining the democratic system of the United States.
Unlike Canada, the US states are responsible for conducting state elections.
In this sense, the majority of American governments have enacted new laws since 2009 that make the process of registering or voting more difficult.
This phenomenon has gained importance after the November 2010 elections, which saw 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
As a result, 180 bills were introduced in 2011 alone that restrict the exercise of the right to vote in 41 states.
The new election laws require voters to present a photo ID and proof of U.S. citizenship.
In addition, these laws also reduce the time limits for early voting, invalidate the right to register as a voter on election day and deprive citizens of the right to vote for which a court record is in place.
Before the 2006 election, no U.S. state required voters to show photo ID.
Indiana was the first state to make such a demand.
In 2008, the U.S. Supreme Court upheld the constitutionality of Indiana's law.
The Republican authorities were quick to extend this practice to other states.
Over the past two years, they have promoted bills in 34 states that would force voters to show photo IDs.
It is important to note that, unlike Quebec, US citizens do not have a universal identity card like the health insurance card.
In fact, 11 percent of the American people, 21 million eligible voters, do not have a photo ID issued by a government agency in their state.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 do not have such a card.
However, it is often more than a hundred dollars to obtain the necessary identification.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and people with low incomes.
In fact, 25% of African-Americans, 15% of those with incomes of less than $35,000, 18% of citizens over 65 and 20% of voters between 18 and 29 do not have the required photo ID.
This goes even further.
Students who are considered to be voters, who are increasingly voting for democratic candidates, are not allowed in several states to use their photo ID issued by their institution.
On the other hand, the same states allow members of fishing or hunting clubs who are more Republican-leaning to use the cards issued by those clubs for elections.
Prior to 2004, no state required proof of citizenship for voting.
Arizona was the first state to introduce such a requirement.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove their U.S. citizenship.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting the Hispanic vote.
Because it's obvious that two out of three Hispanic voters prefer the Democratic Party.
In addition, Republican lawmakers in eight states in 2011 pushed for laws abolishing voter registration on election day.
In addition, you have restricted the right of individuals and groups to assist those voters who wish to register.
These restrictions are not without consequences.
For example, the voter registration campaigns in the 2004 general elections helped to register some 10 million citizens.
The measures adopted since 2009 have led to a 17% decrease in the share of registered voters in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican legislators in five other states have passed laws aimed at shortening the period for early voting.
For example, in the 2008 Florida general election, 33% of the early voters were African-American, despite making up only 13% of the state's electorate.
The same is true of the Hispanic population.
The latter represented only 11% of the electorate, but 24% of the citizens who voted in advance.
In contrast, whites, who made up 76% of the electorate, made up only 46% of the early voters.
Of course, the democratic legislators and their supporters have vigorously opposed the passage of laws restricting voter registration.
Several bills have been blocked by the vetoes of the Democratic governors.
The Attorney General of the United States has intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
They were able to partially limit the damage.
For example, only 16 of the 34 states have passed laws requiring the presentation of a photo ID.
However, the new rules introduced in 2012 will undoubtedly make it more difficult to exercise the right to vote.
Democratic critics denounce the partisan nature of the passed laws and see in them a clear aim to influence the results in the 2012 states.
A 2011 Brennan Center report shows that those states that passed these laws account for 171 of the 270 votes required in the Electoral College to win the presidency.
It is too early to confirm with certainty that these changes to the electoral system legislation will have a significant impact on the outcome of the 2012 presidential elections.
But one thing is certain: these new rules will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, these measures are partly undermining the democratic system of the United States.
