The Higgs boson is being analyzed
The announcement of the probable discovery of the Higgs boson caused quite a stir last summer, and for good reason.
In fact, it is believed that this boson is involved in nothing less than the mechanism responsible for the mass of all objects in the universe.
And finally, it's the last particle whose existence was predicted by the Standard Model -- our best or "least false" explanation of the nature and behavior of matter -- but has not been empirically observed.
But physicists are not entirely sure that it's really the Higgs.
We know without a shadow of a doubt that we have a real new particle and that it is very similar to the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
Moreover, this seems to be confirmed by new data presented this week at a major physics conference in Kyoto, but there is still no data to be absolutely sure.
Let's assume that it's the Higgs, because there's a very small risk of being wrong, and let's see what it's all about.
There is a law in this world that is inevitably unavoidable, which means that two objects cannot be present at the same place at the same time.
It is not possible to break this rule - and don't try too hard, because you will hurt yourself.
Because even if particle physics is a really strange world, it turns out that it also has a similar law: the Pauli exclusion principle, which states that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state", which "state" consists largely of some of their properties.
Based on this, physicists divide particles into two categories.
In one corner are the good citizens, known as Fermions, who politely obey the Pauli principle.
And in the other, the bosons move, an evil gang of anarchists who hold nothing sacred -- certainly not this principle, which means they can actually be in the same place at the same time.
These bosons, according to the Berkeley Labs website The Particle Adventure (which is absolutely amazing, by the way), are divided into two groups: the mesons, which we won't discuss here, and the "force particles" that propagate the great forces of nature, to which the Higgs boson would be related in some way.
But it's important to note that these bosons aren't all as exotic as you might think.
If you are able to read this chronicle, it is only because of a boson of extraordinary banality: the photon, or "light particle", which is the "messenger" of the electromagnetic force.
When an electrically charged particle accelerates or changes direction, the electromagnetic field is "disrupted" at that very spot, much like a pebble thrown into a pond.
This "disturbance" produces an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.), and this wave is nothing but a photon and thus one of the bosons "carrying the force".
Stable field
The same thing happens with the Higgs boson, except that another field, the Higgs field, has to be "disrupted" for this boson to show up.
However, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field; the pathogen must reach very high energies, somewhat comparable to a frozen pond, the surface of which could only be shattered by a very large rock.
So you need a giant particle accelerator like CERN - the Large Hadron Collider is a ring with a radius of 27 kilometers! - to reach these energies.
The electromagnetic field analogy is again helpful in explaining the relationship between the Higgs and mass.
It's not really all particles and not all materials that interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do this, but others do not - for example, a sheet of paper would never hold on to the refrigerator by itself.
And not all particles interact with the Higgs field equally: those that do have a mass, while the others (like the photon, by the way) have no mass.
What can all this research be "good for", asks Mrs Plamondon?
For science, they serve to verify the Standard Model (SM), and they also enable physicists to examine precisely any discrepancies between the observations and the predictions of the SM.
There are, by the way, many physicists who are eager to find such discrepancies, since the slightest difference could open the door to a "new physics" and plug some holes in the model.
It must be said that the latter has still major flaws, since it offers no explanation for gravity (ups!) and dark matter, which makes up about 80% of the matter of the universe (ups again!).
However, such discrepancies have not been found at CERN.
Effects
The impact of this research on the general population is more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there is none.
By the way, in the early 1960s, the pioneers of laser at Bell Labs never imagined that their work would spark such a revolution.
They saw scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, the late physicist Willard Boyle, who worked at Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in the 1960s, and who developed the first permanent laser in 1962 -- the first pulsed ones -- told us that the laser was initially seen as more of a "laboratory toy".
I mean, imagine what...
In addition, applications can also arise from all the instruments surrounding research.
For example, in 1969, Willard Boyle, while working in optics, developed a small light sensor.
Although not the original purpose, this sensor now serves as the "eye" of all digital cameras around the world, and it won him the Nobel Prize in Physics in 2009.
Of course, this doesn't mean that the activities of the LHC will necessarily change our lives, but it does mean that you can never really know.
Palliative care is the best way to die.
With its Committee on Dying with Dignity, Quebec recently discussed the delicate issue of the end of life.
The debate must resume shortly, although a draft law is being prepared.
However, much remains to be done in this important area.
Le Devoir has tried to look into this.
A few weeks ago, Mr. L. was living alone in his apartment in Montérégie.
The cancer of the prostate, which had consumed him, had given him two years to live.
"You gave me five years to live, I've made it seven", he said halfheartedly, lying in his bed at the Victor-Gadbois hospice in Beloeil, where he had arrived the day before.
"It's always a shock, though, and you can't be prepared for it", he says.
The disease is doing its work: an immeasurable weakness prevents him from going to the toilet alone and even eating himself.
Sitting at a table for a delicious lunch, he resignedly agrees to be helped with the meal.
He even manages to smile and talk to the strangers who are busy around him, bringing him his medication, and offering him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
"My greatest wish is to have my diarrhea cured, because it is humiliating", he says.
A few hours later, the team found a cure for this malady.
"In the course of our lives we learn that a man urinates standing up", says Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist at Victor-Gadbois Home.
For some people, returning to childhood is an unacceptable humiliation.
"It depends on the person's ability" to take a step back, he notes.
Because, according to several people who work in palliative care, big events are happening in the midst of these setbacks.
The patients who are admitted to the Victor-Gadbois Palliative Care Home all have cancer.
They have a maximum life expectancy of three months.
At this stage, they are no longer overwhelmed by the so-called "healing" care of the doctors and nurses who care for them.
For Mrs. A., 89, the worst fear is "to die consciously and by suffocation".
But through the illness, I really got to know my children.
"I have good children", she adds.
"I have no more desires in life", she says before accepting a mask to help her breathe.
She is still expecting a final visit from her son, who is coming from Italy, in the next few days.
The Victor-Gadbois home offers a group of volunteers to help with body care and food intake.
Palliative care is used when there are no other options.
To make dying more pleasant.
In Quebec, there is one bed for palliative care for every 11,700 inhabitants.
That's not much, considering that one day we're all going to die.
Here life continues under the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the home's doctors.
Both in terms of physical, emotional and spiritual comfort.
The dying person is given a mouthwash with brandy or Pepsi, depending on his wish.
Diabetics no longer have to control their blood sugar levels.
And death is part of everyday life.
Last night we served Mr. X a beer, and he died during the night.
This morning his son will drink the beer at the feet of the deceased.
"We help both family members and patients", reports Nathalie Savard, director of care.
There's no day like the next at Victor-Gadbois.
Next to a 93-year-old man enjoying the last family gathering in the yard, well supported by his pillow as his honour is stomped, a 36-year-old man dies tragically, surrounded by his parents, his wife and his two young children, after trying everything to survive.
"For six months now, three to five beds have always been occupied by cancer patients under 45 years of age", says Dr. Christiane Martel, worried.
53% of the patients admitted to Victor-Gadbois Home come from their place of residence, 47% come from the hospital.
Problem of access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, that is, care designed to alleviate the suffering of patients at the end of their lives, whether at home, in a hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the Victor-Gadbois Home and the Society for Home Palliative Care in Greater Montreal, specialize more or less exclusively in caring for cancer patients.
It is precisely this major deficiency in Quebec's health care system that has caused several palliative care doctors to be concerned about the passage of a law regulating assisted dying and assisted suicide.
Since October, a manifesto has been circulating, signed by prominent palliative care figures such as Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, expressing their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, Quebec's health care system is not capable of ensuring that everyone has the right to high-quality palliative care before accepting the transition to assisted dying.
Recently, she says, I saw a patient who spent 14 days in the emergency room in great pain, with no relief measures taken.
I'm afraid the only reason patients want to die is because they don't get proper health care.
And at the same time, several oncologists are treating their patients to the very last day despite the worst prognosis.
Hélène Richard's chances of survival were already slim when she stopped a grueling chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was going to stop the treatment, she told me that she was sorry that I was giving up the fight, she told me.
She told me I was finished!
Not omnipotent care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who have asked to die thank the nursing staff for not granting their wish after their pain was relieved by a palliative care team.
But it must be made clear that palliative care is not omnipotent in the treatment of pain.
According to Elsie Monereau, director of palliative care at the Home Palliative Care Society of Greater Montreal, 8% of patients do not respond to pain treatment.
Thus, at the very end of life, doctors often resort to terminal sedation, which involves putting the patient into a coma either sporadically or permanently until the time of his death.
We can no longer pretend that we do not perceive this side of suffering.
Patients without pain relief will increasingly have the option of using this terminal sedation.
Patients whose pain is not relieved all say the same sentence: "I want to die".
But that doesn't necessarily mean, "I want you to put me to sleep", but "I want my pain to be relieved".
