Bitcoin makes it possible to pay and sell without a bank
The opposite of the current monetary exchange based on central banks, identified transactions and processing fees between participants.
Moreover, as is often the case with these technologies, there is a political vision: the belief that the current monetary system, shaped by banking monopolies, is leading to financial crises.
In fact, Bitcoin, invented by Satoshi Nakamoto (a pseudonym), is both a virtual currency (but convertible into dollars, euros, etc.) and a secure exchange protocol like BitTorrent, which allows for the direct exchange of files.
With 15,000 computers on the network, some 200,000 transactions have already been recorded.
A few thousand websites accept Bitcoin as a donation or as a means of payment.
After hitting a high of $30 (€23) in June 2011, Bitcoin fell to $2 five months later before recovering to around $10 today (the prices are listed on the bitcoincharts.com website).
Nothing particularly impressive compared to the world trade in real currencies or financial products.
Nevertheless, the European Central Bank (ECB) has shown interest in this in a report on virtual currencies published in October.
She describes Bitcoin as "the most successful virtual currency", "competing with the dollar or euro" and "similar to conventional currencies".
Bitcoin is different from other types of virtual currencies such as the "credits" used to advance in a video game, which can be won or bought (and sometimes exchanged back) through games.
The social network Facebook has also developed a similar system.
However, the trading is controlled and processed by a central authority each time.
With Bitcoin, all nodes are simultaneously account book keepers, auditors, money issuers, and buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Every transaction between two users is actually between two e-mail addresses in the form of an e-mail.
The difference is that the user can choose a different address for each payment, which ensures anonymity.
A number of the data related to this transaction is electronically signed by a double encryption system.
This allows the network to verify the authenticity of the transaction.
The content of the file also makes it possible to ensure that the traded bitcoins are present in the public account book distributed throughout the network.
The crucial step is to enter this new transaction in this book.
This is done by a mathematical problem that is started on the computers, with the winner, who is a kind of provisional central banker, having the privilege of adding this extra line.
It is a fragmentation of the file, i.e. the conversion of a large file into a shorter and clear electronic fingerprint.
The computers take the new transaction and add a number to it before the whole thing is hacked.
The aim is to find the number that gives a particular fingerprint (many zeros at the beginning).
Once this number has been found, the other nodes can easily check whether it is the correct one.
The transaction is thus permanently linked to the chain of all other transactions, and any modification would alter the fingerprint.
If a user tries to pay twice very quickly (less than 10 minutes) with the same money, only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network and the other would remain unlinked, as both have different fingerprints.
The computer that solves the puzzle gets 50 bitcoins.
In order to prevent inflation, this reward will be halved periodically, probably before the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is limited to 21 million, but it is divisible by one hundredth of a million, which leaves some room for manoeuvre...
In addition, the difficulty of the task increases with each improvement in computing power.
The life of the network has had its ups and downs.
The websites that provide services for Bitcoin were attacked and the Bitcoin deposits were stolen.
"The vulnerability used does not affect the protocol itself", assures Pierre Noizat, who has just launched Paymium, a real-money payment company that uses the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also reports on the possibilities of money laundering through this anonymous service.
However, cash also has these shortcomings.
