Pierre Noizat, who is also the author of a book on this currency, believes strongly in the potential of this technology as a transactional network.
His system Paytunia is equivalent to a credit card (with real money) or a contactless payment with a mobile phone, but uses Bitcoin to validate transactions, which is cheaper.
In addition, the owner manages his identity and can thus remain anonymous.
The system can be easily implemented by the dealers, who do not need to install new terminals or computer programs.
You simply need to provide an address that can be "photographed and recognized" by a phone, says Pierre Noizat, who claims to have thousands of users.
There is a general trend towards a rethinking of hierarchical systems in favour of more horizontal systems.
"It will take some time for Bitcoin to take hold, but 2013 could be a turning point", he predicts.
The ECB's report, incidentally, envisages reassessing the various risks which are now considered high in the event of a success of this currency.
