A Constitution with a Brechstag in Egypt
It is a new poker game by President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt remains more divided than ever over the constitutional declaration that temporarily grants it unlimited powers, he has decided to put everything on the map.
To everyone's surprise, he announced on Wednesday that the constituent assembly would adopt its final version the next day.
The President of the Council has given this plenary session two months to complete its work.
Egypt has now been relying for almost two years on a provisional text, amended several times, which weakens institutional stability and leads to legal confusion.
This new initiative has only caused an even greater division of the country.
For his opponents, the president continues in his "autocratic delirium" by continuing to "break his word" and "trample the law underfoot".
Its proponents assure that it is a way of ending the institutional and political crisis as quickly as possible and speeding up the transition process.
A referendum should be held within 14 days.
A very short period of time, forcing the brothers to abandon their plan to explain the text to the Egyptians paragraph by paragraph.
For the president, it's also a way of regaining his public and democratic legitimacy as protests rage across the country.
According to confirmations in an interview with the American weekly Time, Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote willingly.
The fact that this haste is an ultimatum to the Egyptian people: "Either you vote for my draft or I retain unlimited power" is supposed to put an end to the latter after the adoption of the Constitution.
The 85 members of this constituent assembly, who are mostly Islamists, passed the text yesterday in a strange atmosphere.
The majority of the Liberals have not complied with the call.
Shortly before the declaration of the constitution in mid-November, they turned away, believing that they had not been able to make their views known.
Representatives of human rights organizations, religious minorities or civil society have acted in the same way.
I am not going to go into detail on the matter of the Commission's proposals.
Some are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
It is not surprising that the articles were adopted mostly unanimously.
By the way, the commentators found it amusing that the only difference of opinion of the day was expressed in the time of the prayer, as some members of the committee felt that the pendulum of the Constituent Assembly was not going on time.
The text, which was adopted yesterday evening, consists of 234 articles.
Article 2, which has attracted all the attention, remains identical to that of the 1971 Constitution, stating that "the principles of Sharia are the main source of law".
The Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is an important demand, hoped to replace "the principles" with "the rules", which would have allowed for stricter application.
For the Islamists, the fact that this article has not been amended is a sign of their goodwill and respect for other members of Egyptian society.
The Liberal Group, which regards this as a mere propaganda blow, responds with "hypocrisy".
Because according to them, the Islamization of the constitution is done through other articles.
They are particularly concerned with Article 220, which gives Al-Azhar University an advisory role, particularly in relation to the verification of compliance with Sharia law.
According to Egypt expert Sophie Pommier, this is worrying because "the people who are asked to give their opinion are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
Here you can see the first signs of a theocracy".
The Liberals' fears are also fuelled by the fact that the next rector of this university is likely to be far less moderate than the current one.
"There is no concrete religious commitment at present.
With this constitution, we remain within the framework of the bourgeois state.
Most of the jurists who worked on this text are not ulema, but academics who were partly trained in the French system", says Alexis Blouet, who is writing a doctoral thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
It admits, however, 'that there may be ambiguity with regard to Article 220, since the terms used are taken from religious vocabulary.
The reference here is particularly to the "fiqh".
And in the future, the question may arise as to the extent to which civil judges are competent to rule on this".
The text adopted yesterday is being strongly criticized, apart from its religious aspect, because of the far-reaching powers it confers on the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood argues that these are significantly reduced compared to the former regime.
Another point of contention is the powers of the army.
In accordance with the military's wishes, the defence budget is not being examined by Parliament but by a national defence council.
The Commission has also proposed that the European Parliament should be consulted on the matter.
The latter also express their fears about the text, which they consider a threat to their freedom.
The fact that blasphemy is still a crime and that insults are now prohibited could have serious consequences for the right to freedom of expression, especially for the press.
Moreover, no article is about women's protection, underlines Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
In your view, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture by Article 36.
This word was not in the previous Constitution.
While the Egyptian president was due to speak on television last night, demonstrations are planned for this afternoon.
The supporters of the head of state will march on Saturday.
In Israel, Ukrainian tourists expect holy sites, the navel of the world and a sea of salt
The Promised Land combines the glory of Bible truths, modern comforts, and unspoiled nature.
AIF gives you the top five reasons for visiting Israel.
Worshiping at the Holy Places
Visit the Jordan River, where Jesus was baptized.
It is said that all who bathe in this river receive God's blessing.
Galilee is the place where Jesus performed his miracles, turning water into wine at a wedding feast, walking on water, calming a sea storm, and catching fish.
It was here that Jesus appeared to his disciples after his resurrection.
Most of the sanctuaries, however, are in Jerusalem.
The faithful make the way of the Passion or the way of the Cross of Jesus Christ (in Latin: Via Dolorosa).
The path begins at the Roman fortress of Antonia, the Praetorium, where the court was, and leads through the streets of the Old City to the Church of the Tomb on Mount Golgotha, where the crucifixion site, the anointing stone, and the tomb of Jesus are located.
In Christian view, this is the navel of the world, symbolizing the salvation of mankind.
The Monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem stands on the spot where, according to Christian legend, the tree from which the cross for the crucifixion of Jesus grew.
Jerusalem is also home to the holiest site of the Jews - the Wailing Wall, the remains of a temple that was destroyed by the Romans in 70 C.E.
Traditionally, people of different faiths leave wishes behind, which are then fulfilled.
Taking a Trip to the Heights
The ruins of the fortress of Massada are the remains of the secret hiding place from enemies that Herod the Great had built for his family in 25 A.D.
They lie on a rock face in the mountains, 450 meters above sea level.
Only mountaineers can reach the ruins on their own.
Everyone else will take an aerial cable car to this historic summit.
The famous Hermon ski resort, located at an altitude of 1,600 to 2,040 meters (1,600 to 2,040 feet), attracts countless tourists during the winter months.
From the foot of the mountain, you can get there by shuttle bus.
The total length of the ski slopes is 45 kilometres.
According to an ancient legend, pagan gods were said to live on the mountain top.
Visiting Unique Museums
There are almost 300 museums in this country.
One trip is not enough to see all of them.
But at least five of the most interesting of them should be visited.
One of these is the Israel Museum, near the Knesset (parliament).
It houses ancient Qumran manuscripts, or Dead Sea Scrolls, found in caves in the Judean desert, as well as some 500,000 archaeological and anthropological artifacts.
The Museum of Art in Tel Aviv is also worth a visit.
The collection of works by the Impressionists and Expressionists Monet, Pissaro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso is exhibited there.
In Akko, you can visit the museum at Bad Al Basha, which houses several halls of old Turkish baths with sculptures of visitors and bathers of the time.
In Caesarea, you should visit the unique private Ralli Museum, where you can admire sculptures by Dali and Rodin.
There are no museum guides or souvenir shops.
Admission is free, and donations are generally rejected.
The fifth museum, the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv, tells the story of one of the most shocking chapters in history.
The most moving section is the Children's Monument, erected in memory of the 1.5 million children who perished in the concentration camps and gas chambers.
When you enter the room, it's completely dark.
The stars are shining.
And it's got the names of the Jewish children and the countries where they died.
Ukraine is also mentioned.
Doing Something for Your Health
Israel's three main recreational areas are located on the shores of the Mediterranean, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
Each of the three sites has swimming pools, water parks, dolphinarium and oceanarium.
Amazingly, the Red Sea is also used for bathing during the winter months, since the water temperature does not drop below 21°C and the air warms up to 23°C.
The Dead Sea is even warmer, and bathing is done there year-round.
Incidentally, this unusual sea, at 1,300 feet [417 m] below sea level, is the deepest sea in the world.
Its turquoise-blue water is highly saline, so even non-swimmers can easily get to the surface.
The surrounding landscape is indescribably beautiful.
Visitors come here for saltwater and saline treatments, as well as for treating skin inflammation, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes, and to soothe tired nerves.
The secrets of antiquity touch
These secrets are kept in the old city of Tel Aviv, the city of Jaffa on the Mediterranean coast.
The famous sea route connecting Egypt, Syria, Anatolia, and Mesopotamia passed through this city.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and Egyptian legends.
According to legend, Noah built his ark here, and Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda here, leading a long and happy life with her.
Tourists like to wander through the narrow lanes, which are named after zodiac signs.
Fortuna is said to be the hero of all who touch the walls in the alley with their zodiac sign.
In Jaffa, you can meet newlyweds from all over Israel and even other countries for photo dates.
In Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can wander through the Roman theater and capture the fortress of the Crusaders.
In Roman times, Caesarea was the most important city in Judea and the residence of Roman governors, including Pontius Pilate.
The carefully restored theater now hosts evening concerts and operas.
Tourist shopping list
If you go to Israel, don't worry about your poor English: About 30% of Israelis speak Russian.
Instead of taking the money in euros, take it in dollars, which can be easily converted into shekels (current exchange rate: 1 dollar to 3.8 shekels).
In the city, you usually get there by bus, but there is also a high-speed tram in Jerusalem and the only six-station metro line in the country in Haifa, which connects the city centre with the city centre.
It's actually a subway.
A journey within the city costs 6 shekels, regardless of the means of transport, which is enough for a journey of up to 1.5 hours, including transfers.
According to Jewish tradition, Saturday is the Sabbath day in Israel.
From Friday evening until sunset on Saturday, markets and shops are closed and public transportation is suspended.
And Sunday morning is the start of the work week.
Many cafes, restaurants and taverns serve only kosher food, which excludes pork, seafood, shelled fish and food containing both dairy and meat products.
Instead, you can choose from a variety of dishes, including ham and beef, soups and desserts (made with coconut milk), traditional Jewish hummus paste, various sauces, fried dumplings made with mashed beans and peas (falafel), and fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs in the streets of Israeli cities.
But there are plenty of well-fed cats that roam the streets comfortably and unimpeded.
At night, they are even seen sleeping on the roofs of parked cars.
Cats like busy places and don't say no to treats.
A rental car costs between $37 per day (Hyundai Getz) and $188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80) depending on the brand.
Insurance costs an extra $15 a day.
And bike rental costs 15 shekels a day.
Museum tickets cost an average of 30 shekels.
In numbers
In 2012, more than three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel.
Most adventurers and recreation seekers came from Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England, the United States, and Ukraine.
From January to October 2012, 118,8 thousand Ukrainian tourists visited the Promised Land, an increase of 51% compared to the same period in 2010, before the lifting of the visa requirement on 9 February 2011.
"The Great and Powerful" leads to Moscow: Migrants save money on language
While MPs and civil rights activists debate the benefits of the mandatory language test law for migrants, criminals are already trading with fake certificates
Each year, 13 million migrant workers come to Moscow, St. Petersburg, and other cities in Russia.
Most of them are citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their sole aim is to earn money for the support of the families who remained at home.
On 1 December, a law came into force requiring all migrant workers to pass a test certifying knowledge of the Russian language.
The scheme is currently only applicable to migrants wishing to work in the service sector, in municipal housing and in retail trade.
However, the Federal Migration Agency is planning to make the tests compulsory for all migrant workers in the future.
It is not only language tests, but also tests on Russian history and the foundations of legislation.
Language skills must be demonstrated both for obtaining and for renewing the work permit.
Exceptions apply only to citizens of countries where Russian is the official language.
The same is true of persons who obtained their diplomas and certificates before the collapse of the USSR in 1991.
Meaning, problems and protection of rights
All the examination centres will be under the aegis of the Pushkin Institute of Russian Language, the Russian University of International Friendship, the Moscow State University, the St. Petersburg State University and other Russian higher education institutions.
Migrants can take the tests in all cities, and more than 160 centers have already been opened in Russia.
The initiative to introduce the tests was supported by the deputies of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Agency.
On the other hand, before the law came into force, civil rights activists repeatedly asked the following question in the press: What is the point of the whole thing?
What changes are being made to the requirement to demonstrate language skills, both for Russians and for foreign workers?
The main aim, according to a spokesman for the Migration Agency, is to reduce the number of forced labourers.
"Many people are talking about protecting the rights of migrant workers", says Viktor Sebelev, head of the Federal Migration Agency's representation in Tajikistan.
However, their rights must be protected before they leave.
Only an organized recruitment will solve 90% of the problems of foreign workers.
Migrants without employment, education, language skills and medical advice face problems.
Sebelev is convinced that a future migrant without language skills will inevitably encounter people with evil intentions who will put him in a dark, cramped barracks under the pretext of help, where he will endure for months without food and documents, working 12 to 14 hours a day with dozens of his peers.
We get a lot of complaints from our migrants.
"At home, you are promised the same thing, and when you arrive you are cheated, your passports are taken away and you do not get the promised salary", confirms Tolib Shwaripov, head of the main labour migration department of the Tajik Migration Agency.
Don't you dare call me that, boss!
Yet many citizens of Central Asian republics who want to earn their living in Russia admit that they not only do not speak the language of the country they are going to, but they can hardly express themselves in their own language.
Of course, this is not so much their fault as the bad: few Turkmen, Uzbeks and Tajiks can afford even a decent basic education.
Because their families do not even have the money to feed the children, let alone to buy them decent clothes, shoes and school supplies.
As teenagers, these children immediately seize their first opportunity to make money.
"It's difficult without language skills", they admit.
"You feel humiliated and inferior".
Civil rights activists stress the following important aspect of the law.
Only legal immigrants have to take the test.
If you don't have that status, there's no exam and therefore no official job.
Meanwhile, most of the migrant workers are still in Russia illegally.
"Welcome" or "No unauthorized entry".
Many migrants confirm that it is not easy to obtain official status in Russia.
The reason is bureaucratic obstacles and, of course, language difficulties.
In addition, legalization costs money: 12 to 16 thousand rubles.
A fake registration can be made quickly and for only one and a half thousand.
The Russian police know that our documents are mostly fake and we are not registered, and that this leads to cases of blackmail.
"They want one or two hundred rubles for cigarettes and tea", Tajik Umed Huschkadamov told reporters.
"Just don't be afraid of the costs of fake papers"
The day the law came into force, it became clear that it wasn't just the registration documents of migrants that could be forged.
Some false certificates certifying completion of the language test have already been seized by employees of the Federal Migration Service.
The forged papers were printed with a regular color printer.
Of course, the new owners did not receive it for free: Each migrant who hoped to spare himself the tests paid seven thousand rubles for the document.
This is more than twice the cost of the official test: it costs a migrant worker three thousand rubles.
Both officials and civil rights experts agree that the most important immediate task is to protect the system from corruption so that the certificates cannot be bought easily.
For the moment, the authorities can only promise guest workers who fail the test for the first time that they will be given time for a basic language course.
In addition, newcomers without language skills are offered jobs in areas where active communication with people is not necessary.
Home Office ignores illegal arms trade
Legal weapons very low in crime
The Russian Interior Ministry is planning to tighten the gun laws for private gun owners.
This is the response of the authorities to recent events: the shooting at weddings and the killing of seven people in the Moscow murder of lawyer Dmitry Winogradow.
Police are proposing to ban nonlethal weapons in public and raise the age for gun ownership from 18 to 21.
The proposal was supported by the Chairperson of the Duma Committee on Security and Anti-Corruption, Irina Yarovaya, who promised that the amendments to the gun law would be presented to the Duma shortly.
Not everyone is happy that the Russian authorities want to tackle the problems by "pulling the screws".
An open letter has been posted on the Internet, in which the authors - representatives of various arms associations - call on the authorities to refrain from "senseless escalations".
The percentage of crimes involving registered weapons is very low, criminal lawyer Vasiliy Lesnikov told the BBC's Russian service.
According to the statistics of the Ministry of Interior, 142 crimes involving the use of registered weapons were committed in the six months of 2012, while for the same period a total of 1,168 thousand offences were recorded.
The authors of the open letter are convinced that tightening the law on private gun ownership will not deter criminals from profiting from the black market.
According to the authors, at present in Moscow you can find any weapon for little money.
Meanwhile, the Interior Ministry stresses that the spread of illegal weapons is under control.
Suppliers: from factories to officers
The guns are getting onto the black market through multiple channels.
There are five main channels, says former colonel Viktor Baranez, who spent ten years in the Ministry of Education and the General Staff.
Screenshot of a website accepting weapons orders
The first channel is the army, i.e. weapons stolen during the fighting in the Caucasus.
"The weapons were stolen by both the Russian officers and the Caucasians themselves", says Baranez.
On channel two, illegal weapons are being stolen from law enforcement officers by criminals.
Baranez explains that these include weapons stolen both from police armories and directly from law enforcement officers.
Other illegal weapons are from military stockpiles.
Explosions were frequent in many military camps.
"There is evidence that in some cases, arson was used to cover up the absence of weapons", says the former military officer.
According to Baranez, the arms manufacturers also contribute to the black market.
"Today, there are countless private arms factories that cannot withstand international competition and therefore dump the weapons on the black market, such as in Moscow", reports the expert.
Another channel of the black market is smuggling.
Especially many pistols and rifles come from poor countries like Kyrgyzstan.
"There is a production of its own, sometimes by hand, and a mafia that organizes the smuggling", explains the former military man.
Where did the guns come from?
Experts calculated the approximate share of each of the five channels in supplying illegal weapons to the black market.
In 2011, a report was prepared by the Centre for Problem Analysis and State Administration.
The experts analyzed reports from the Ministry of the Interior and the Federal Service for State Statistics, criminological literature and publicly available data on portals on weapons.
The vast majority of illegal weapons, according to investigators, come from the army and law enforcement agencies.
Half of all guns on the black market are "the fault of those responsible for their work with guns", says the report.
The researchers found that 17 percent of the weapons were from conflict zones, 14 percent were stolen from the production of weapons, and 5 percent were illegally mined.
A sales consultant at an arms store, who declined to be named, assured that weapons found in illegal excavations have long since been discarded because they are outdated.
He says it's more common for dealers to get their supplies from an arms warehouse.
An ensign is used to buy a weapon, such as a TT pistol.
The gun is exhibited and passed through the fence.
"The dealer brings the gun into town and sells it there for 900 euros apiece with two magazines", he says.
"The police, of course, know everything, so when they cannot follow the crime detection plan, they periodically conduct control purchases from dealers who sell illegal weapons", the sales consultant adds.
"Like in the luxury store"
Buyers and sellers are most likely to find each other through acquaintances.
I was looking through websites and blogs when someone noticed me and suggested that I come to the Begowaja station, where a person would wait for me, who would take me to a certain place where we could negotiate the price.
I didn 't know the price of the gun until I was there .
Military commentator Viktor Baranez
"To get a gun, I need someone I know who has contacts", says the salesman. "I have an acquaintance like that, but I don't trust him".
There are dealers in the markets, but you have to go there and make an appointment with a code like "by Ivan Ivanovich, who sends out the message that the daughter has lost a tooth".
I'm actually getting some leads right now about a guy I know and trust.
He's only supplying me with the rings because he knows I'm not gonna give him a shit.
Newcomers look for weapons in different ways.
Former military man Viktor Baranez was trying to buy illegal weapons in the mid-1990s when he wrote an article on the subject.
The schemes have not changed, he says.
He got a photo album with "anything" in it.
"I felt like I was in a luxury store", recalls the military man.
According to Baranez, the buyer doesn't get the cat in the bag, but can try everything.
I, as a potential customer, don't just buy, I drive the salesman into the woods, and we set up a target.
"I can shoot there, and when I am convinced that the gun has a good shot, we negotiate with each other", the expert describes the procedure.
Shopping from the sofa
Internet search engines show results of websites and groups in "Vkontakte" where weapons are offered "for various purposes".
No paperwork is required, and there are no face-to-face meetings.
"You just need the right amount of money", says the advertisement on the website "Buy a Rifle or Pistol".
It's where users place their orders and make inquiries.
Is it sold to minors?
"Of course without a license", user "Iwan" asks (literal quote).
