"The brain is only moderately deceivable so far"
The subject of augmented reality, which is popular with modern technologists, has recently been seen through the lens of special glasses.
Google first presented a working model at its annual conference in the summer, and then in November it was announced that Microsoft had also filed a corresponding patent.
However, speaking to Shahram Izadi, head of the Interactive 3D Technology Group at Microsoft Labs in Cambridge, it is clear that the glasses were just a transit station for the company's scientists.
It is exciting to be able to manipulate virtual objects in the air with your bare hands and create virtual open spaces.
- Please describe briefly the research your group is conducting.
- We are dealing with the interaction between man and machine, but we want to extend the boundaries of this interaction.
So far, humanity has been stuck in the phase of working with pixels on flat screens, which are sometimes touched.
But we want to look forward to five to ten years and predict the radical changes in this interaction.
For example, the Xbox console and the Kinect sensors are a step forward, and nowadays no Xbox is sold without Kinect, because everyone is interested in motion control.
- What's the future?
- Although Kinect has brought interaction to a physical level, much of it still takes place on the flat screen, sometimes in 3D.
The input of information (the system receives more data) has been improved, the output has not been decisive.
We're trying to change that, working on real three-dimensional representation systems based on various technologies, including projections.
We need to unlock the computer world into our physical world and make it more tangible.
This requires not only the user but also the environment.
We could then more easily supplement the real world with virtual objects.
And first of all, we should get rid of this stupid virtual reality helmet!
- What do you think about voice control?
She's popular, but isn't she overrated?
- It is certainly not the all-purpose solution, as it raises questions about privacy, because you do not always want to inform everyone about your actions and intentions.
Actually, any kind of interaction with computers is good, but each in its own particular niche.
For example, we worked on a project in the area of controlling objects in public places, where we experimented with short and concise gestures instead of overloading.
The gestures were not recorded by the camera, but by a bracelet that recorded the movements of the bones and muscles.
It is still relatively large, but theoretically it could be reduced to the size of a wristwatch.
But overall, the future is mixed control, such as gestures and language.
- What do you mean?
- We'd ask you to hand me this can of spray?
You're saying it and you're implying it.
- I usually just say it.
- Oh, that would be very hard to tell.
- You mean you want the user to adjust to what a machine can do at a given time and what it can't?
- Not necessarily, but this is about a mutual rapprochement.
I think that in the near future we will have to work mainly on developing new types of sensors that allow us to record people's reactions more accurately.
These can be, for example, laser sensors, because they provide good resolution at depth, which is very important.
What are your claims based on your work with the Xbox Kinect sensors on modern cameras?
Is it lacking in resolution, depth, or something else?
- The current generation is basically a good starting point for our work in the field of three-dimensional detection.
Of course, 8 megapixels at 1000 fps would not be bad.
But the important thing is not the megapixels themselves, but the quality of the matrix and the depth.
So, all the current technologies are not good enough for us, because the developers of the algorithms have more work.
The resolution along the X and Y axes must be taken into account, as must the resolution along the Z axis.
The speed and number of frames per second are also important.
The human movements are extremely dynamic and frankly, the current 30 fps are not enough, especially for gestures.
Stephen Betishes developed a touch sensor in our Redmond lab with an adjustable processing delay between 1 and 100 milliseconds, with today's commercial sensors closer to the second value (60 to 100).
Not everyone understands how much this affects human-machine interaction.
For my work, I needed a device just like this, only without touch control and with more images per second.
- Shouldn't we increase the number of cameras?
- Kinect is currently working with three "cameras", one of which is actually an infrared transmitter and the other a receiver for the reflected signal.
And the third camera is actually a regular RGB camera.
It's not used to calculate the depth of the object.
More cameras might solve the problem...
Or amplify the problem, because more calculations would be necessary.
What would be great is a flexible, Kinect-like system where we could play with different camera angles to see how that helps us in three-dimensional positioning.
- If I remember correctly, Microsoft, unlike Google, did not present its glasses to the public.
Don't you think that in terms of the application of augmented reality technology in everyday life, the best prospects are in glasses?
- Of course, it's not comfortable to always hold a smartphone in your hands while you're on the road, but I think this is the best option: an augmented reality "switch" where we can switch from glasses to the smartphone via a cloud.
The glasses are a personal gadget and that is their strength (private ones can only be seen by you), but also their weakness, because augmented reality using glasses prevents you from working with others on virtual objects.
- Let's imagine for a moment that the manipulation of virtual holograms in the air is accessible not only to Tony Stark from Iron Man, but to normal mortals as well.
There is a problem that critics of this idea often point out: there is no tangible reaction!
My hands feel nothing at all!
What answers does your group want to give to this objection?
- In my lectures, I often talk about augmented reality as the seventh breakthrough in human-machine interaction.
I think the eighth breakthrough could very well be the integration of tactile perception.
An interesting method is currently the use of the second hand as a somewhat unusual projection medium.
She's a great pressure sensor!
But there are also technologies that are actually designed to give the "pictures in the air" something hand-held, for example, the interference of some directed ultrasonic rays at a certain point where the finger is, produces a feeling, but at the moment it is still as faint as someone blowing over the palms of the hands.
There are also bands for the wrist that affect the nerve endings in the fingers, which is also a potential direction.
- Have you tried to trick the brain?
Make it think it feels what it should feel when it's looking at something?
- That's a good idea. We haven't tried that yet.
Here is another challenge we will have to contend with for a long time: to make a person believe that he is physically in a closed space, but instead in an open, practically infinite space; here we are working on concepts with treadmills (other than in gyms), moving platforms and large balls.
So far, the brain has been only moderately devious, and we have many years of hard work ahead of us.
And that's what makes working in virtual reality so attractive to a researcher: we're just getting started on a lot of things.
