NKÚ chief: Control of the black system fails because of politics
The Czech Republic has good control bodies and adequate legislation on public procurement, but falls short in its application.
In an interview with Aktuálně.cz, the vice president of the Supreme Control Authority (Nejvyšší kontrolní úřad, NKÚ), Miloslav Kala, said that the government is not in a position to control the situation.
"A law is never perfect, but it must be applied correctly - and I don't think that's the case here", Kala comments on the current situation.
A similar result appears to have been obtained by a joint check by Czech and German inspectors.
As a negative example of practice, he cites the attitude of Prime Minister Petr Nečas towards the so-called "black system".
Recently the Prime Minister said that the ODS would not burden the entrepreneurs with controls - so is the system now prohibited or allowed?
"A law must have its validity, and if something is prohibited by law, then the prime minister cannot just come and obstruct the control authority, whose duty is to control compliance with the law", Kala notes.
At the meeting of the Committee on Audit of the Chamber of Deputies you spoke of a joint Czech-German project to compare the laws of the two countries on public procurement.
What was the point?
This is a parallel test which we started about two years ago.
In short, it is the European legislation that determines how public procurement is to be handled, and national legislation builds on this, and finally, there is the actual practical application.
We have compared all these with each other and although the examination is not yet complete, we have found very interesting differences.
This confirms that it is not enough to keep drawing up new and more precise rules, but that we must also look at the actual application of the law.
How can the project help you? What do you think about the results of this project?
It is precisely such joint control that could help us to stop constantly trying to perfect the laws and to lower and lower thresholds when it does not seem to be having a particularly positive effect.
Economy means buying something at a reasonable price (which is not always the lowest price) and excluding unlawful enrichment or even criminal acts.
But lowering the thresholds for orders does not guarantee that we will achieve this goal.
It may even be that we are only overloading the system with paperwork in this way, and those who are looking for loopholes in the system will find it much easier to exploit the system than if the thresholds were kept higher.
They talk about the problems in the practical implementation of the Czech law on public procurement.
How does the control system work in Germany?
Is there a similar authority here to our NKÚ, or does the system work differently?
As far as the authorities are concerned, the German counterpart to the NKÚ is the Federal Court of Auditors, which is similar in structure to ours and also has a college, which is only slightly different in form, but in principle both authorities work similarly.
The powers are also to some extent comparable, but Germany is a federal state, which means that there are these accounting offices in the individual federal states - this is where the German system differs from ours.
The BRH is only allowed to control federal funds, which is equivalent to our state funds.
The public funds managed by the districts and municipalities are subject to the control of the Land Accounts.
As far as German legislation is concerned, is it simpler than ours?
I would not like to compare this without specific information, but Germany is often called a model in some respects, although it is certainly not possible to say that Germany is better in everything.
Is it because the examiners are better there?
I'm not sure, but as I said, I don't like comparisons like that.
It should be noted that those countries which are a model for us also have problems.
Otherwise, they wouldn't have any cooperation with our agency, would they?
As regards the Czech legislation, what significance has the amendment of the Public Procurement Law had for your authority? Do you feel any impact?
Given that this amendment has been in force for only a short time, it has not yet had an effect on our examinations.
Since our checks are carried out at a later date, we must expect a delay.
The impact of the changes will be felt more in the preparatory phase of future checks - we have introduced the new control instrument 'Detection of uneconomic risks' and have used it to examine and analyse almost 14 000 public contracts - where the changes will naturally have an impact, as the thresholds change, the conditions for certain types of tenders have been modified, etc.
Do you see the passage of this law as a positive thing, or will the system be burdened with more bureaucracy?
I think that this law is definitely a step in the right direction and I hope that this assumption is confirmed.
However, the problem may arise that the rules become "stricter" and can no longer be observed.
Under the previous rules, the persons subject to an audit are accountable to the institution (for example, in the case of an operational programme of the regional policy, the Regional Council) in that any non-compliance with the procurement law amounts to a breach of budgetary discipline.
But does it make sense to make the law even stricter?
I don't think that's the way it is.
The system must exclude those who want to attack and abuse the system, and not punish those who have made a formal error that does not affect the actual decision-making.
Such a system only puts the bureaucracy under even greater pressure.
Where's the way out?
Let us first say which path is not conducive.
The Prime Minister recently said that the ODS would not burden the entrepreneurs with so-called "black system" controls - what does that mean exactly?
Is the black system now prohibited or allowed?
The Commission has not yet decided whether to grant the aid to the Member States, but it has already decided to grant it to the Member States.
He can say, "We'll change the law and allow it", but he can't say that we're pretending like nothing happened.
The law on public procurement contains relatively strict rules on the formal execution of certain operations - and this is also true for the protection of public competition.
On the other hand, it is also tragic when the best bidder is excluded solely on the grounds of formal errors.
The law will never be perfect, but it must be applied correctly - and that is what I think we lack.
