Šimon Ornest: We want to collect positive energy at our concerts
What do you think about the end of the world in less than a month?
This is one of those disaster reports that we humans are so eager to jump on.
We're more of a joke about this with our band, The Tap Tap, and we say that we're the only band in the world that can gather enough positive energy to stop or prevent the end of the world.
In December, you will also be performing a unique project, with three concerts against the end of the world.
Can you introduce the project to our readers?
It's a nationwide benefit event that we've been planning for two years.
To do this, we want to use the marketing potential of the Mayan calendar, which is predicted to end on December 21 at 11:10 a.m.
On the day before, i.e. 20 December, three concerts will be held simultaneously in Prague, Brno and Ostrava from 21:00.
The concerts are supposed to end around the time when the Mayan calendar ends on the Pacific island of Kiribati, which is 12 hours ahead of us in a time zone.
Who came up with this idea?
Originally by me, we then worked on the idea with our graphic designer Honza Augusta.
We want to not only gather enough positive energy to prevent the end of the world, but we also want to think with the public about the state of the world we are going to leave to our children.
To mark the end of the Mayan calendar, we have also developed a unique collection of shoes, T-shirts, bags and key chains against the end of the world, which people can also support us by purchasing via www.e-tap.cz.
The Tap Tap also recorded the so-called "Doomsday Anthem" with other artists.
The anthem is already very popular on YouTube. Will it be heard at the benefit concerts?
Of course, and that's all the way to the end, assuming everything works out and the end of the world doesn't happen...
The hymn is to be sung by all the performers at all three concerts simultaneously.
The anthems will also be broadcast live on Czech television.
The lyrics of the anthem are by Tomáš Hanák, who also plays the main character of Jesus in the video, also Xindl X sings with...
How did you come to work with them?
We also cooperate with other personalities of the Czech cultural scene, which is related to the fact that we realize many charity events and concerts...
We try to involve these people in our projects.
And it turns out that most of them are interested in working with us, and they enjoy it.
What purpose does the proceeds from the concerts against the end of the world serve?
For the establishment of the accessible educational centre Studeo, which we have been working on for six years together with the Tap Association at the Jedlička Institute.
Students at the Jedlička Institute are regularly supervised by lecturers who help them with various leisure activities.
Since the students themselves do not have the means to visit the editors, we want to help them in this way.
The Jedlička Institute will be completed with a separate building, which we will move into with this project.
Each concert features several groups and performers.
What criteria did you use to select these?
We wanted to put together a program that appealed to all generations, including children.
In Prague, for example, there are Chinaski, Support Lesbians, Illustratosphere with Dan Bárta, The Tap Tap, Marián Bango and Jiří Suchý.
More information is available on the Internet at www.kpks.cz.
Are similar "big events" planned for the future?
In May we will perform for the first time at the Prague Spring, and for this concert we are preparing an interesting program with interesting guests.
We would also like to perform at the Czech House in New York next year, and I personally would like to combine this with performances in Washington and Chicago, if we are already in the United States.
Your plans abroad are not small, you have performed in Madrid, Brussels, London or Moscow.
But the Tap is a group made up of people with disabilities.
How do you manage these trips logistically and organisationally?
It's not as bad as it seems at first glance.
Five of our members are wheelchair users, so the wheelchairs have to be carried in the trunk, and of course we have to carry a lot of instrument cases and other luggage...
Nevertheless, it has always worked without any problems so far, ČSA and British Airways have always been very well prepared for us, that I have sometimes wondered in part.
Even in Moscow, where we were recently, there were no problems.
Your trips abroad will give you a comparison of how accessibility is in different countries, how people with disabilities are treated there, etc.
How have you experienced these things?
After Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other cities where everything works better than here, we have just witnessed in Russia that everything in the East is still in its infancy.
Compared with Prague, Moscow is not at all handicapped. There it is still unusual for someone in a wheelchair to be alone in the city center.
It is not even a matter of course to leave a wheelchair user in an elevator, for example.
Fortunately, there are also groups that try to draw attention to the problems of people with disabilities.
And in what ways must we catch up with the more developed countries?
There are many things we are still hanging on to...
It should be noted, however, that the improvement of the situation is always dependent on the efforts of those concerned.
In London and Madrid, it is absolutely common for people with severe disabilities to move around in public spaces, go to museums, use toilets, etc.
It is not uncommon for a larger group of disabled people to participate actively in social events, and we are a bit ahead of the West in this with the band The Tap Tap!
Respect in public and accessibility is one thing, but only when we have great athletes, artists, actors, politicians or lawyers in our ranks will things really start to change.
So far, these are only isolated cases of particularly strong-willed personalities.
The Tap is very popular right now, but if we go back a few years, what motivated you to start a band in 1998?
At that time I started as a tutor at the Jedlička Institute, where I met many young people who were interested in doing something intense.
And since I am a musician myself and play saxophone among other things, I started a music company with a colleague.
Well, over time, as our presenter, Láďa Angelovič, likes to say, things got a little out of hand. (Laughter)
But the band only became known in the last few years, or am I wrong?
It is true that working with well-known singers has helped us; in addition, we have also started to actively promote ourselves.
We've come to realize that when you do something and you can't see it from the outside, your performance doesn't exist in a sense.
The EU funding also enables us to afford good editors, high-quality equipment and so on.
Was it your goal to make it this far with The Tap Tap?
From the beginning, I felt the potential to approach things differently.
In show business, one person often copies another.
This is logical in its own way, since everything new is considered with caution and is not accepted until after a long time.
There are very few things that are truly unique, and I dare say that Tap Tap is one of them.
The first impression that the viewer usually has is of course pity; that is only natural...
But this compassion is absolutely superfluous, because people with disabilities are not lonely and abandoned creatures that we should feel sorry for.
They are people who can live and develop fully, provided they have the means to do so.
I always say that when people with disabilities succeed, it's not just a breakthrough for them, it's a breakthrough for society as a whole.
Was it also helpful to this success that you are a strict boss, as many people have heard?
If you want to do something well, you must not compromise in many things and you must also demand a certain discipline.
I think this is perfectly normal.
Some come to us with romantic ideas, and when they find that they have to rehearse twice a week, go through preparation stages, and spend a lot of time on tour, then the enthusiasm fades quickly.
But that's how it works everywhere, in any band that's serious about working and trying to get something done.
The Tap Tap currently has twenty members.
How many of them were there from the beginning, i.e. since 1998?
There's only one:
We're an open group, people come and go, you can't stop it.
Anyone who has the will and the desire to participate is always welcome.
