Poland and space.
Last week, at a ministerial meeting of the European Space Agency (ESA), Poland was admitted as the 20th member of the European Space Agency, making it the second member from the former Eastern bloc (after the Czech Republic, which joined ESA on 12 November 2008).
Poland began a close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and participated in several ESA projects in the following years.
Poland's journey into space began much earlier, of course.
Even before World War II, Polish space enthusiasts were interested in space travel, but they did not always understand it.
I recall, for example, the lecture given by A. Šternfeld at the Warsaw Observatory on 6 December 1933, in which the author presented ideas from his pioneering work "Introduction to Cosmonautics".
The young engineer's ideas (born 1905) left the audience cold, however, and after years Šternfeld still remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski had shown interest in his work.
Šternfeld won the Prix REP-Hirsch, founded by Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch, in 1934 for "Introduction to Cosmonautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899-1966) later became an important advocate of astronomy and space travel.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and wrote several books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski's worldwide recognition for his contributions to space exploration was recognized, among other things, by naming one of the craters on the far side of the Moon after him.
As early as 1925, a railway dray was built in Poland, with a rocket propulsion system planned.
Unfortunately, the author of the draft and the details of this project remained unknown.
It is not even clear whether the rocket should be used to launch or to slow down the Draisine.
The information on this comes exclusively from the contemporary press.
In 1933, the Polish infantry began to deal with rocket-propelled shells.
The research was carried out by the Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia Institute in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Prof. Gustaw Mokrzyckiegi.
The documents submitted show that the research had progressed to the stage of practical tests.
The research was interrupted by the German invasion.
In 1937 the design of a photoelectric fighter rocket by Ing. Rohoziński appeared in the trade press, and the following year the work "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by author Leliwa-Krzywoblocky appeared.
Both projects concerned the military use of the rocket propulsion system.
Shortly before the war, all projects for the military use of rocket technology were coordinated by the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy).
The Committee was established in 1937, but after two years of activity its work was interrupted by the outbreak of war.
Further articles on space travel appeared in the Polish press after the war, thanks to the work of the Polish Space Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
The first mention of this company is in the November 1954 issue of the magazine Problemy, in which four extensive articles are devoted to space travel.
The article by Prof. M. Subotowicz contains the proposal to establish a space company.
At that time, the first satellite projects were underway, and it was clear that space exploration would have a future.
From its very beginning in 1956, the Polish Aerospace Association (PTA) sought to join the International Federation of Aerospace, which was founded in 1951. In fact, the PTA became a full member in the autumn of 1956.
The following year, the first PTA chairman, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902-1959), became vice-chairman of the International Federation for Space.
He held this office until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the PTA has been instrumental in the development of the highly successful meteorological rocket (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), the first Polish rocket for scientific research.
The first type, the RM-1, was completed in 1957, and the first launch took place on 10 October 1958.
The missile, which had a maximum flight altitude of 1,800 m, was about 80 cm long and weighed less than 5 kg.
Later an improved version, the RM-1A, was built, and in 1959 flight tests began in the Błędów Desert with the RM-2 two-stage rocket.
The missile was 1.4 meters long and weighed about 11.5 kilograms.
A further stage of development should already be capable of carrying out real scientific work - the RM-34 missile should reach a flight altitude of up to 14.5 km and be used for observing high winds.
However, in 1962 further development was stopped.
The successor to the first RM-type missiles was the Meteor-1 missile, developed between 1962 and 1965.
The missile was designed as a two-stage missile, its total length was 510 cm and the launch weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types of this missile were developed (Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C), differing in the size of the space for transporting scientific instruments.
The Meteor-1A missile had a carrying capacity of 0.4 litres, Meteor-1B of 0.34 litres and Meteor-1C of 0.62 litres.
The maximum flight altitude of all three types was 37 km.
In the years 1965 to 1968, the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Aviation Institute, the first flight tests of which began in October 1970.
Meteor-2 had a take-off weight of 380 kg and was capable of carrying a payload of 10 kg to an altitude of about 60 km.
Later versions of the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 were built.
It is also worth mentioning that Poland joined the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960, followed two years later by the creation of a national COSPAR committee.
Poland also participated in space exploration with Soviet satellites under the Intercosmos programme, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second Intercosmonaut after the Czech Vladimír Remek.
