In November 1979, a mob of protesting Islamist students occupied the U.S. Embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats hostage.
For their release, they demanded the extradition of the deposed Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who had fled to the United States after the revolution, which had maintained patronage over his regime for decades.
The American government had no positive way out of this situation - it could not afford to throw the Shah overboard, as this would have seriously damaged the confidence of its allies in other countries.
At the same time, it was unable to secure the release of the hostages in Iran, where the revolution had led to the establishment of a theocratic regime.
It was a severe blow to the reputation of the United States, and the ensuing failure of the violent attempt to free the hostages only made matters worse.
The diplomats who were captured were finally released after 444 days, after negotiations brokered by the Algerian government.
The fate of the hostages has triggered a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian sentiment at home.
The Iran debacle was a major contributor to the defeat of Jimmy Carter over Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film Argo by director and actor Ben Affleck describes an episode of this story that gave the United States a small partial victory.
Immediately before the occupation of the embassy, six embassy staff managed to escape.
This ended after numerous complications at the residence of the Canadian ambassador.
The CIA, in cooperation with the Canadian authorities, managed to get the refugees out of Iran, using an extravagant story to conceal their true identities - they were traveling with Canadian passports disguised as members of a film crew who were supposedly visiting the country to film a science fiction film.
Combination of genres
The plan, developed by "Exfiltration" expert Tony Mendez, also required the cooperation of Hollywood.
To make the cover credible, articles about this film project appeared in trade magazines, press conferences were held, and the fictitious production company had a real office.
The details of this operation have long been kept secret, but the film is based on the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck's film is a special combination of several film genres.
On the one hand, it is a realistic political thriller, but at the same time it is also a so-called "Caper Movie", i.e. the story of a successful Husari play such as the film Ocean's Eleven.
This changes the mood of the film - on the one hand, the documentary scenes from Tehran (the title sequence shows iconic contemporary photographs, and there are no major differences in the filming of the same situations).
On the other hand, the loose passages from Hollywood, which ironically and slightly over-the-top come from here.
And then there are the scenes from CIA headquarters and other institutions -- men in suits at the conference table, in the hallways, on the phone...
Ben Affleck has made a remarkable career comeback with this film.
From a mocked actor he has become a respected director, and as an actor he is no longer the object of ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film after the crime thriller City Without Mercy (2010).
It is also Affleck's first film not to be set in the director's hometown of Boston.
The sense of place was one of the features that set this director's previous films apart from the standard Hollywood.
Affleck also demonstrates this sense in Argo, where Tehran is "played" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film take place in the streets and show the reconstruction of events that really happened - the opening sequence of the assault of the embassy is very impressive in its clarity, yet it conveys the feeling of confusion and unpredictability that occurs when the story moves somewhere.
Affleck and his team are also doing a similar thing with fictional scenes (the fake film stick in a Tehran bazaar).
Too much action in too many places
The director also had to deal with the fact that the story doesn't actually offer many cinematically exciting scenes.
But he works with the few quite successfully, sometimes helping reality - which doesn't always seem so elegant (the scenes where the impending crisis at Tehran airport is averted by a phone call in America, or the pursuit on the runway, seem somewhat fabricated).
The weakness of Argo is its too wide dispersion, which is due to the need to show too much action in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman are very charming in their roles as Hollywood employees, but their characters deserve more space, and that makes them far from alone in the film.
Affleck's film loses some traction, and it's a film that you can watch with a certain amount of interest, and yet enjoy the design and the retro style that reminds you of a thriller from the '70s.
But it is hard to get excited about it.
But it is enough to remind us of a piece of history that is still alive in a way and to prove how exaggerated the ideas of the all-powerful and all-knowing secret services are.
Guidelines for balloon inflation, bananas and circuses
The www.bankovnipoplatky.com server, which annually puts out a survey on the most absurd bank charges, has decided to hold the contest "The most absurd regulation or idea from the EU workshop" this year.
"We came up with this idea after the recent EU plan to introduce a 40% female share in the management of large European companies", said Patrik Nacher, who organised the survey, to the newspaper Právo.
The Commission has also been asked to submit a proposal for a regulation on the protection of workers' rights in the event of a breach of the rules on the protection of workers' rights.
Until then, women enjoyed an advantage in life insurance because they were objectively less risky to the insurance companies.
"Further incredible ideas from the EU workshop can be nominated by the end of this year.
The actual vote will take place by the end of February 2013", Nacher said.
Controversial EU regulations include the mandatory addition of bioethanol to fuels, which is harmful to the environment, the ban on reliable mercury thermometers, simply because they contain a relatively small amount of this dangerous substance, and the chicken cage size directive, which has made eggs much more expensive this year.
In the past, the de facto prohibition of the use of the term 'butter-based ink' and the prohibition on the sale of conventional light bulbs have also been criticized.
Bananas must be 14 cm long
The EU apparatus often decides under the pressure of one or another lobby of trade and industry, whose demands are usually represented in Brussels by one or more member states (the Czech Republic, for example, is currently trying to enforce the demands of Czech banks even by veto).
Lobbying interests also advocated that bananas of the highest commercial grade in the EU must be at least 14 cm long and not have a 'curvature anomaly'.
The European Commission defended itself by arguing that it merely harmonised the disparate national standards which would impede trade.
The EU has already softened the standards for fruit and vegetables, despite the opposition of some countries, with the indication that the existing directives would lead to food waste.
One candidate for victory in this survey may be the EU regulation from last year, which requires balloons to be sold with a warning that children under the age of eight cannot inflate the balloon without adult supervision.
The EU cited an American study which found that balloons are the leading cause of death by suffocation among children.
A similar restriction already applies to children under 14 years of age when using annual crops.
Curious ideas are also at home
A directive which concerns European officials themselves is also relatively absurd - anyone holding an official position in the EU is not allowed to use the name Macedonia because of the sensitivity of the subject to Greece and must instead say FYROM (Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia).
The server Bankovnípoplatky.com, in cooperation with the association of liberal economists Laissez Faire, nominated the EU regulation on the scope of food stocks in the territory of a member state, in addition to the other absurdities.
The EU thus set the maximum volume of food stocks that could be on the territory of the Czech Republic on the day of our accession to the EU.
The Czech Republic, for example, then exceeded the prescribed volume for canned mushrooms, for which we were threatened with a heavy fine.
The survey organizers were also impressed by the idea that certain countries should receive money for not having a sea, or the idea of giving grants to applications for grants.
These ideas, of course, did not come from Brussels, but from Prague.
"We are at a disadvantage because we do not have an ocean.
We will apply to the EU for a refund", declared Jaroslav Palas (ČSSD), then Minister of Agriculture, in autumn 2004.
The argument was that the cereal harvests were very high and that the State stocks were overcrowded as a result of the so-called intervention purchases.
Since the Czech Republic has another way to sea ports, the EU should pay us hundreds of millions of euros, according to Palas.
The European Commission finally went so far as to organise a tender for the purchase of cereals from countries with no access to the sea.
The Commission has also proposed that the Commission should be able to provide the Commission with the necessary information to enable it to carry out its tasks.
EU: Bizarre regulations are the exception
While regulations are easily the target of criticism in the Member States, the EU's efforts to regulate and thus to improve the effectiveness and development of the European Union as a whole are, in the opinion of some experts, more deserving of recognition.
The Commission has also been asked to submit a proposal for a regulation on the protection of the environment, which is to be adopted by the Council on 1 January.
