"People want me to save the Republic, but I'm just an amateur", Okamura claims.
Senator, how did you come up with the idea of running for president?
I'm not about being a senator or president.
If everything in our country worked without problems, I wouldn't run anywhere.
But I can't stand to see the Republic being looted for 20 years, thieves running around free, while people are being raised in taxes and retirement age.
I had no ambitions to become a politician.
But if I see something I don't like, I try to suggest a solution to change it.
And since I'm over 40, and independent and nonpartisan, I have no other way to make a difference than to run for the office of a senator or president.
You made it to the Senate, and then you headed straight for the castle.
You're not turning your back on your constituents?
I've been telling myself all along that I'm gonna take up the fight for the castle after the results of the Senate elections.
I later clarified this and said that I would run for the office of President if I was elected Senator.
But my goal is not function, it's a tool that I can use to realize my visions.
I need as much influence as possible and as strong a mandate as possible.
The difficulty is not only that we as a people curse in the pub and on TV, but that we crush anyone who wants to change.
In addition, the media, which seeks to rob you of your honor, confuses freedom of speech with freedom to lie.
For example, I was alleged to have bribed journalists or to have been an adviser to Jiří Paroubek.
Let's talk about your visions.
You have taken up the fight for the castle with the thesis of the material and criminal liability of politicians and with retroactive declarations of assets of 20 million crowns.
You'll have to change the law.
As President, you have no authority in this respect, and only the Senate as a whole can bring in legislation.
How do you want to solve this problem?
As a simple citizen, I have advocated that the tour guide should remain a free trade, and this has been achieved.
The problem is small-minded politics - when someone from the right or the left comes up with a good proposal, it is deliberately rejected, and that only holds the population back.
As an independent non-party, I have a much greater potential to win support from all the parties represented in Parliament.
My advantage is that I can take what's best for our country from either party without any paperwork or party dogma.
Do you see yourself as a person who is more right-wing or left-wing in politics?
From a Czech point of view, I think people see me more on the left.
But for me, this right-left thinking is completely irrelevant.
It's important to me that we move on.
I don't care if someone is on the left or the right; I want to connect people.
I have always publicly supported any good solution, whether it comes from the KSČM or the ODS, and I will also oppose bad ideas.
You don't like being called a populist.
But don't you confirm that with what you just said?
When you create a business plan in a company, you also have an ideal goal and a vision.
And that's the one you want to approach.
I think you can call this populism, but all the proposals I've talked about are already working in the world, or they've been discussed by important experts.
But without support in Parliament, you're left with slogans.
And that's not going to get you anywhere in politics in the long run.
Or do you think that if you talk to people long enough, you'll be able to enforce, for example, material and criminal liability?
I don't have any other choice.
To convince politicians, journalists and the public and try to get them on our side to push through these goals.
As President, I would have no problem in calling on the leaders of the parliamentary parties to establish by law the material and criminal liability of politicians, officials, judges and prosecutors.
And then the respondents might have to say why they are against it.
A strong personality who points out wrongs can put pressure on the political scene.
Just take the direct election of the president, which was a merit of public pressure.
I'm not a genius or an intellectual.
I'm trying to find allies for my views and visions.
I have just started in politics and I am trying to find the support of the majority for my programme.
I always try to judge things myself, and if it doesn't work, I'll go back to the private sector in six years.
That sounds a little like Okamura saving the Czech Republic.
I'm not a saviour.
I know that I can't do anything alone, so I've talked to several well-known people about whether they want to run for the Senate.
I have spoken to Radim Jančura, for example, but he refused because of the workload.
I also supported the investigative journalist Jana Lorencová, who exposed the fraud in the light fuel oil trade.
I started my candidacy with the assumption that people were deeply dissatisfied, but now I'm not sure.
Sixty percent of those eligible to vote have not voted at all, and those who have voted have mostly voted for establishment representatives.
That leaves us two independents in the Senate.
The people have chosen such a composition of the Senate that changes will be very difficult to enforce.
But I'm going to fight for my vision, like direct election of mayors and district mayors.
Are you thinking about starting your own party?
I haven't thought about it yet because I don't have time to check the past of every potential party member, and I don't even have the money for it.
I don't even have money for the presidential campaign; there are only 20,000 CZK in my transparent account.
You don't have any money?
You're talking about asset declarations. What did yours look like?
I estimate my personal wealth at about 60 million CZK.
In Prague, I have a land worth 25 million, an apartment worth about 10 million, another for 8 million, an art collection worth about 10 million, an Aston Martin worth 3.5 million and a Škodu Superb worth about a million. And then I have a few more millions on my account.
The Aston Martin was a childhood dream, by the way. I always liked James Bond, the way he drove the car, the way he was gallant with women and the way he fought evil at the same time.
You drive an Aston Martin, you're worth 60 million, and you don't have any money for your campaign?
You say you want to change the Republic, but you don't want to invest your own money in it.
That's not very convincing.
I don't have 15 million for the campaign.
You want me to go into debt?
I've already put $2.5 million into the campaign.
The fact that I don't have sponsors shows that my program probably doesn't get much interest.
And I'm not obligated to fund the campaign out of my own pocket.
The campaign costs are basically covered by my salary as a senator.
But I could not live on the senator's salary alone; nor could I finance my son's English school, which costs 30,000 a month.
If I was just trying to make money, I wouldn't run for anything.
So you're going to stay as an entrepreneur to make ends meet?
Didn't you say you were going to withdraw these activities?
But it's not about the amount of the salary.
As promised, I've partially reversed my activities.
For example, my deputy will become the managing director of the travel agency in the spring.
People want to see me as a Samaritan saving the Republic.
But I have to make a living.
What monthly income were you used to as an entrepreneur?
About 200,000 to 400,000, and it's still going on.
But as president, I would stop my business altogether.
