The MVRDV architects prove that the real adventures are not only in the head - with the example of Spijkenisse and the recently built Bücherberg - 2 photos
"I find the building fun, it looks futuristic, and there's something interesting to see again", says Lisette Verhaig, a passerby on the side of the road.
And Stefan Spermon, an IT technician at a large local company, says, "Yeah, it's nice, the house".
But I wonder what we need a library for today.
They all have the Internet, iPads and e-books.
No one volunteers to go to one of those old-style libraries anymore, do they?
Spijkenisse, a sleepy little town just outside Rotterdam, is a strange record holder.
The municipality of 80,000 inhabitants has the lowest education rate in the whole of the Netherlands.
To counter this stupidity, a few years ago it was decided to help raise awareness and to recreate the seven fictitious bridges depicted on the euro banknotes as beautifully painted miniatures of reinforced concrete.
The success of the educational campaign was limited.
And so the city fathers realized that there was only one way to become a master of statistics: a library!
Winy Maas from the Rotterdam architectural firm MVRDV, a master of the bold beam diagrams and producer of funny, even often cynical buildings, took the matter with his usual calmness and appeared at the competition hearing in 2003 with five books under his arm and a smile on his face.
And while the jury was still looking around in stupor and shrugging its shoulders, the cowardly Maas piled his exquisite contributions of greatness into a pyramid and ended his actionist-backed speech with the words: "Dear city council!"
That is my proposal for the Spijkenisse Book Mountain, the so-called Book Mountain!
Nine years later, the 30 million euro mountain is uncovered.
It is part of a revitalization project which also includes a garage, supermarket, post office and a few adjacent residential and row houses with a total of 50 apartments.
In early November, the Bücherberg was awarded the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
The project is also nominated for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
This is the faceless small towns, which until then had nothing to offer but a postmodern pedestrian zone and an incredibly ugly town hall, behind whose white facades one would be inclined to suspect a dairy factory, to enrich a piece of contemporary architecture.
But most importantly, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in its history.
The long road to the book
First impression: a book-eldorado with a cheese bell.
Although there is an elevator that leads through the middle of the mountain range, the real joy of space and reading comes from walking up the topography.
The interior is bright and clear, the burnt brick floors and the elegant street lamps speak the language of a public square.
The urban ambience is perfect.
They're already looking for park benches, dogs and boys and girls playing football.
And everywhere there were books, books, books.
"The bookshelves are usually along the facade, and in the middle is a large, dark room, which is usually uncomfortable and impersonal", says Winy Maas.
We've reversed the traditional room configuration and turned the reading area inside out.
The interior of the book mound is cleverly used: in the middle are offices, an Internet library, a chess club, an environmental center, and a home technology center.
A special delight are the black bookshelves, which are sometimes wall cladding, sometimes trim, sometimes stair rails.
Optics, touch and smell are foreign.
Even seasoned architects and civil engineers are shaking their heads at the unknown building material.
"We wanted to work with recycled materials", explains Joop Trouborst, project manager at the municipality of Spijkenisse, at the request of the Standard.
And so one day, in a farm in Friesland, we came across a suitable agricultural waste product.
For many years, a millimeter-thin plastic film has been used as a root cover in greenhouses and fields in the Netherlands.
It's cheap and time-efficient.
The thin fabric lasts for two seasons, then it's ready for the garbage bin.
For the library, the fleece was pressed to four-centimeter-thick plates - the first time in this quantity.
Under heat and pressure, the so-called land-based plastic (KLP) discolors into a dark, homogeneous, resilient material that smells a little like a new car and a little like a sports shoe.
After 105 steps, you reach the summit.
At the end of the nearly 500-meter trek, the literature café not only offers a fantastic view of the city but also Dutch croquettes and stuffed fig trees.
They provide atmosphere, but most importantly, the right humidity in the literature mountains.
Donations for the new soul
"It's hard to believe, but despite the many glass surfaces, this house is an ecological landmark", says Trouborst.
Heated and cooled with geothermal heat.
Although the Bücherberg is under a glass cascade, the sun shines only briefly in on sunny days.
The wide wooden glue bands that cross the glass facade serve as shade and capture much of the sun's radiation.
The room's climate is very pleasant.
The rest is done by fully automatic rollers.
Stefan Spermon, the initial skeptic in the IT industry, has already ventured into the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was there too.
And so does the TCM teacher Cynthia Bogarde, who even calls the Boekenberg a "long overdue soul" of spice.
The reason: At the opening a few weeks ago, each resident was invited to donate a book from his personal collection.
The aim is to fill the gaps in the library, which is not yet fully equipped and currently has 70,000 items.
The concept has taken off.
The shelves are full to the top.
"Nothing is worse than a half-sized library", says architect Winy Maas.
"I think that thanks to our invitation, every resident now has a certain relationship to this new house.
Everyone knows his book is part of this building.
And if it's just for show.
This has enabled the MVRDV to achieve what is known in the technical jargon as the "founding of identity".
Spijkenisse has written literary history.
Young and uneducated as she may be.
This is finally a starting point for identity.
Szabo: "Germans need to play a bigger role"
Germany abstained in the vote on the inclusion of Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on US-European relations, Berlin balances this on a narrow diplomatic level.
Deutsche Welle: Earlier this week, Germany initially signaled that it would vote against the request for Palestinian observer status at the United Nations.
But then Berlin was in.
Why? Why?
Szabo: Germany does not support what the Israelis did in Gaza.
Germany must be careful, however, because of its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I don't think it supports the American position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence - but without being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained from voting on the establishment of a no-fly zone.
This was finally enforced by NATO.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on important international issues?
Yes, that's right.
That is because it is currently changing its foreign policy, away from a policy that was, so to speak, managed by the United States, towards a German foreign policy.
The European Union has a number of important tasks to fulfil.
So the Germans are in between the fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I believe they are still in their early stages of their role, but they are on the way to a more "normal" foreign policy.
A foreign policy like France or Britain.
What does a "normal" foreign policy mean in practice from the German point of view?
It shows a willingness to take positions on national interests that are independent of those of the United States or European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy is motivated by economic policy, that is, by exports and its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany's economic interests are to a certain extent different from those of the other great powers and therefore Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced the attitude in the Middle East conflict and the vote at the UN?
On the one hand, Germany has large sales markets in the Middle East, particularly in the Gulf States.
So we have to be careful not to embarrass the public, but also the elites in the Arab countries.
That certainly matters.
But I would not want to give too much weight to it either, it is not a completely one-sided relationship.
But it certainly plays an important role in German thinking.
Has Germany damaged its relations with the United States by abstaining from important decisions, such as the vote on Palestine?
I believe that in Europe and even in the United States there is a great understanding of the German position.
I do not think that this was a break as dramatic as the Libyan question.
Perhaps Germany will even show some respect for itself.
It is a sign that it is being taken seriously as an international player and that its interests must be taken into account.
There are different opinions in Europe on the Palestinian initiative.
The United States, on the other hand, has clearly voted for a veto.
Are there differences of opinion between the United States and many European nations?
Because of American domestic policy, these differences have always existed.
I think the Obama administration is probably quite understanding of the European position behind the scenes.
But given the political situation here, the government cannot, of course, publicly represent this position.
I believe that the actual differences of opinion are not as great as they always seem.
If you look at the relationship between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, Obama is not that enthusiastic about Netanyahu's policies.
Is it difficult for Germany to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the United States on the one hand and the position of the main partners in the EU on the other?
I think that's what makes it so difficult for the Germans.
It would of course be a little easier for the Germans if there were a coherent and unified European policy, which is not the case at present.
So they can't be part of a larger line and instead have to push things out of their own position.
That is what they are doing with the euro.
I believe that in the future Germany will play a leading role in pushing Europe towards a European position.
This is not easy for Germany, of course, because of the relationship with Israel.
This has always been a sensitive issue.
But I think the Germans understand that they have to play a more independent role.
Does Germany see itself as an important international player in this role - does Germany want to play a leading role at all?
Or is it still difficult for Germany to lead?
Germany is not yet used to it, it is still uncomfortable and, for obvious reasons, it is still difficult for the country to play a greater role.
If we look at the euro crisis, for example, every time Germany takes on a bigger role, a variety of anti-German sentiments are unleashed.
That doesn't make it easy for the Germans.
That's the old problem, you don't want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
In this respect, Germany is in a much more difficult position than the United States.
It has to be receptive to a wide range of neighbours and opinions, and that's not easy.
The US is steadily losing its influence in European politics, but the EU is not filling that vacuum at the moment. Who else is left?
The Germans will simply have to play a bigger role.
Even if they don't like it, it's uncomfortable for them and makes them even more unpopular - c'est la vie!
Stephen Szabo is deputy director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, an institute where academics and policy experts from Europe and North America collaborate to research the challenges facing the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he has specialized in German politics, US foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
