Facts about sexually transmitted infections
What are the main sexually transmitted diseases?
Bacterial STIs include syphilis, chlamydia, and gonorrhea.
Common viral STIs are HIV, human papillomavirus, genital herpes or hepatitis.
Fleas and ticks are parasitic STIs.
Who are the main groups affected?
Syphilis and Drypoids are most common in men who have sex with men.
The Robert Koch Institute estimates that at least four out of five of all reported cases of syphilis in Germany are transmitted through sexual contact between men.
In heterosexual adults, sexually transmitted diseases such as chlamydia infections, trichomonas, candidiasis (fungus), trippers and human papillomaviruses are common.
HIV prevalence among heterosexual adults in this country is relatively low - yet, about 20 percent of new HIV infections are among this group.
Chlamydia infections are much more common among adolescents than in other populations.
According to European surveys, three quarters of all infections affect young people aged between 15 and 25.
In this country, human papillomaviruses are also common among adolescents.
How have the infections developed?
Not all sexually transmitted diseases are compulsory.
According to the Robert Koch Institute, the number of syphilis infections has more than doubled from 1,697 in 2001 to 3,698 in 2011.
The number of new HIV infections has been declining since 2007.
In 2011, there were about 2700 cases.
This is about a tenth less than the previous year.
What symptoms indicate an STD?
Infectious diseases can cause genital ulcers, urinary discomfort, discharge, abdominal pain, and blisters or warts.
Often, however, they do not cause pain or other symptoms and therefore go unnoticed.
How can you protect yourself?
Condoms may reduce the risk of infection, but they do not provide 100 percent protection.
In some cases, STDs can also be transmitted through lubricant infections and close physical contact.
Therefore, experts recommend regular check-ups, especially for those who frequently change sexual partners.
Early detection can cure most STIs and prevent later consequences.
