Mexico's Enrique Pena Nieto is facing a difficult start
As Mexico's future president Enrique Pena Nieto prepares to take office, Will Grant of the BBC analyses the challenges ahead and the mixed feelings of his people.
Traffic in Mexico City is particularly bad right now.
Even on better days, it is a city that is always clogged, but on Monday a ring of steel was erected that blocks several important transport routes into the capital and creates chaos on the streets.
The aim was not to disturb commuters on their way to work, but to prevent protesters from reaching Parliament.
On Saturday, Mexico's new president, Enrique Pena Nieto, will receive the presidential oath and assume the leadership of the nation.
He is faced with a complex task.
Mexico has been doing well economically under the outgoing government of Felipe Calderón, but the country is in the grip of a drug war that has already cost 60,000 lives in the last six years.
"My administration is strongly committed to reducing violence", Pena Nieto told U.S. President Barack Obama in the Oval Office earlier this week.
I'm going to propose a new security strategy to help us achieve that goal.
Before he was on par with the US president, Pena Nieto served as governor of his home state of Mexico.
In this densely populated, sprawling part of the country surrounding the capital, opinions are divided about the new head of state.
A straight man
For example, in the remote town of Valle del Bravo, people remember him fondly.
Residents of the resort attribute to him the development of tourism and the construction of infrastructure.
To reach the city, one can take one of the highways that Pena Nieto built, a major improvement over the bumpy, bumpy roads that once existed.
His name is also displayed outside a modern sports centre and an impressive interactive museum on climate change.
