But that is what the family has been denied until now.
The authorities treated me as if I were a gossip, a troublemaker, a whiner.
They want you to just accept their judgment and shut up.
"But that's not possible with so many mistakes and omissions", she says.
President Pena Nieto's acceptance of the presidential coup d'état on Saturday also means that he is taking on a great responsibility.
Tens of thousands of Mexican families have been affected by violent crime in the last six years, and the new president has promised to take special care of this problem during his term.
"I hope he is as president as he was as governor", says PRI congressman Olvera in Valle del Bravo.
But that is what the families of the victims in Ciudad Neza fear most.
Prosecutors say Bradley Manning did not complain of abuse
The prosecution denies Bradley Manning's allegations that he was mistreated in prison.
The hearing will focus on Manning's time in military prison in Quantico, Virginia.
The defense is seeking a dismissal of the charges on the grounds of harsh conditions of detention.
The US Army Private is accused of stealing thousands of classified documents
Prosecutors on Friday sought to determine that Army Private Bradley Manning - accused of the largest leak of classified information in U.S. history - missed several opportunities to complain about the mistreatment he allegedly suffered in military prison.
At a cross-examination of Manning during a pretrial hearing at Fort Meade, Maryland, Major Ashden Fein stated that records of weekly visits made by prison officials during Manning's nine-month incarceration in Quantico, Virginia, contained no complaints about his treatment.
One day before the cross-examination, which was held in response to a motion by the defense to dismiss the charge - Manning had already been sufficiently punished by the harsh prison sentence - Manning had testified that he had considered suicide in prison.
The US Army intelligence analyst, arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of classified documents during his service in Iraq.
The material was then released by WikiLeaks on the Internet.
WikiLeaks never confirmed Manning as the source of the information.
At Friday's hearing, Fein reviewed with Manning the forms that officers filled out after meeting with Manning during his detention at Quantico Military Prison, where he was held under enhanced conditions from July 2010 to April 2011.
The officers asked Manning questions and wrote down his answers.
When questioned by Fein on Friday about the forms, Manning admitted that he had rated the treatment by his guards as "excellent" and the treatment by the institution as a whole as "very professional".
The forms, so fine, contained no complaints of mistreatment, even though the officers had questioned Manning directly about his treatment.
Manning replied that he had expressed his concerns verbally and that the officials had discussed them with him and indicated that they were looking into them, but that they had not been recorded.
"They wrote down (after discussing the concerns) 'no problems,' and that didn't necessarily mean I didn't say anything at all", Manning said.
The judge, Colonel Denise Lind, also asked Manning why he did not complain about his treatment when he met with a committee in January 2011 to investigate the suicidal thoughts he had mentioned on a form several months earlier.
Manning replied that his intention during this meeting was to downgrade his observation status to "injury prevention".
The military said it had granted him this restrictive status - one level below suicide risk - for his own protection and that of others.
"I wanted to convince staff that I was doing well and get rid of the injury prevention watch status (...) in order to achieve what I saw as a higher quality of life", said Manning.
Manning testified Thursday about his arrest and transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for nearly two months before being transferred to the prison at Naval Base Quantico in Virginia in July 2010.
He said that in Kuwait he had considered suicide and that he had passed out because of the heat.
Not being able to know what was happening to him or to the outside world was stressful.
"My world shrank at Camp Arafjon, at this cage", Manning said Thursday.
I thought I was going to die in this cage.
When he was transferred to Quantico, Manning had spent most of his days in a small cell - at least 21 hours, often more than 23 hours - and without company.
All he was allowed was a mattress, a blanket, flip-flops, clothes and his glasses.
Manning said he tried to stay active because during the day it was forbidden to sleep or even lie down.
He had to sleep with light coming in from outside his cell.
If he turned around at night and the guards could not see his face, he was awakened so that he could turn around again.
In January 2011, Manning's attorney formally challenged Manning's treatment.
In April 2011, Manning was transferred to the military prison at Fort Leavenworth, Kansas.
On Friday, Judge Manning also questioned an allegation he made in his testimony on Thursday - that he had slept naked in his cell in Quantico one night and had to stand naked before guards and other prisoners at a morning count.
Manning had testified that he never had the opportunity to wrap his blanket around himself during that count.
During Friday's interrogation, Manning said he had inferred from an order from his guard that he should drop the blanket he could have covered himself with, but he admitted that no one had asked him to do so.
On Thursday, Manning testified that he had been forced to sleep naked the night before, and that he had previously tried to show an officer that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning told the officer he could have used the bundle of his underwear or his flip-flops to injure himself, but he didn't.
That night, Manning testified, his underpants, flip-flops and glasses were removed from his cell.
His lawyers hope that the judge will at least take into account his prison experience and drastically reduce his sentence should he be sentenced at his trial at the military court, scheduled for early next year.
The defense has indicated that Manning will plead guilty to lesser offenses while other charges deemed too extreme will be challenged.
The prosecution is expected to provide a justification for the conditions of detention.
The Pentagon remains committed to its position that Manning was held under the same conditions as all other high-security detainees at Quantico.
Manning is charged with facilitating the enemy, illegally posting intelligence on the Internet, transmitting national defense information, and theft of public property or documents.
If found guilty on all counts, he faces life in prison.
My Mexican-American identity crisis.
Many people are forced to leave Mexico because of the lack of opportunities.
Mexicans tend to blame the immigrants - they remind them of hard times, he says
Navarrette believes that Mexican Americans are caught between two worlds.
