Signs pointed to two queues: one for "Mexicanos" and another for "Extranjeros".
I stood there for a few seconds, not sure which one to go to.
I grew up in central California and I've been called "Mexican" my whole life.
An ethnic acronym -- just like my friends in Boston call themselves "Irish" or my friends in New York "Italian".
Later, I decided to go with "Mexican-American".
But this was Mexico.
And in my grandfather's home, there was no need for abbreviations or commas.
I was just an American.
I speak Spanish, at least well enough to assert myself in that language at both ends of an interview.
But I don't have the vocabulary of a native speaker, and I can't get rid of my American accent either.
So I took my American passport and stood in line for foreigners.
I was thinking about that moment this week when the future Mexican president Enrique Pena Nieto visited the White House to meet with President Obama.
The agenda was all the topics that are expected when the heads of these two countries meet: immigration, drugs and trade.
Pena Nieto was also very interested in talking about the growth of the Mexican economy, which is one reason why Mexicans today are just as likely to stay in Mexico as they are to emigrate to the United States.
He wants to ally himself with the United States and Canada and create a North American trading bloc on the model of the European Union.
And Pena Nieto vowed to continue Mexico's war against the drug cartels, even though he didn't give details.
Mexico's relationship with the United States is complicated and full of resentment.
Most Americans probably never waste a single thought on the fact that the United States invaded Mexico in 1848 and forced the leadership of the country under fire to cede more than half of its territory to them.
But for Mexicans who think in centuries and not minutes, memories of this event are not to be missed.
So as soon as a U.S. government official makes the slightest criticism of Mexico, you hear complaints in the Mexican press and among the country's elites about how the Americans are encroaching on the sovereignty of their neighbor.
And the children of Montezuma are on the warpath.
And yet, the biggest challenge for Mexico is actually in its relationship with the more than 35 million Mexican Americans living in the United States.
You want to talk about resentment?
There's more than enough.
Mexico has winners and losers, people for whom the country offers opportunities, and others for whom it doesn't.
The only reason why so many people of Mexican origin live in cities like Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver or San Antonio is that at one point in our family tree, a person -- maybe a parent or a grandparent -- didn't get a chance in Mexico and migrated north.
And in most cases, this person matched a profile -- dark-skinned, uneducated, from a poor village, etc.
We are the descendants of these people, and our allegiance is to them.
Not Mexico.
And while we may be living the American dream, having gone to good schools and getting good jobs, we must never lose sight of the fact that it is the American dream we are living - not the Mexican dream.
Our identity may be obscure at times, but our loyalty is not.
This is clearly the United States.
Moreover, we are aware that many members of the Mexican leadership do not like us.
This is based on reciprocity.
They see us as a memorial to a humiliating defeat and look down on us because we're not Mexican enough.
Our Spanish will never be good enough, our ties to Mexico will never be strong enough.
They think our existence is a symbol of failure.
If our families hadn't failed in Mexico, they wouldn't have left.
And then we wouldn't be trapped behind the curtain now, with a comfortable life in the United States, but still somehow lost.
My wife, who was born in Guadalajara and legally immigrated to the United States as a child, reminds me that there is tension between Mexicans and Mexican Americans because Mexicans have a clearer idea of who they are -- and Mexican Americans take that badly.
