But many Mexican Americans I know feel that they do not belong in either country.
We love the Mexican band Los Tigres del Norte, but we also love Bruce Springsteen.
You get the best of both worlds, but you're not rooted in either.
In Mexico, we're seen as Americans.
And in the United States, we're seen as Mexicans.
As I was to learn during my trip, there is something that makes this relationship even more complicated: Some Mexican leaders and parts of the educated citizenry want to reestablish their ties with the diaspora.
They want to use Mexican Americans as temporary "ambassadors" for Mexico, representing their interests in the United States.
We should tell our American colleagues how great it is to visit this country and pressure the political leadership to intensify their ties with Mexico.
Well, then.
That's not gonna happen.
Too many hurt feelings.
And with the unequal distribution of income, the rampant corruption and the drug violence, many of us are not so sure that this is really a great country.
I'm afraid you'll have to go through it alone, Amigos.
That's fair. I know.
If at least some Mexicans are not yet ready to forgive the United States for the way it treated Mexico a century and a half ago, they must also accept that some Mexican Americans harbor resentment for the way their family members were treated not so long ago.
I'm not sure.
Maybe we're more Mexican than I thought.
Old battles, new Middle East
The ceasefire between Israel and Hamas could prove to be an unexpected pillar of peace
Can there ever be lasting peace between Arabs and Jews in the Middle East?
The recent bloody events seem to be stifling such a hope.
Amid the usual blaming, countless buildings were razed to the ground, more than 140 Palestinians, most of them civilians, and six Israelis were killed - and for the first time, rockets from Gaza hit near the Israeli metropolis of Tel Aviv and the holy city of Jerusalem.
But while Israelis and Palestinians seem trapped in their historic conflict, the Middle East is changing around them.
The Arab Spring has created a new, uncertain situation, and whether they like it or not, Palestinians and Israelis have become part of that chaos.
Maybe this will only lead to more bloodshed.
But there is reason to believe that the deadly stalemate may finally come to an end.
A War That Can Be Neither Won nor Lost
At first glance, optimism seems far from appropriate in view of the current situation.
Even if the ceasefire agreed on November 21 continues, the fighting this week has strengthened the hardliners on both sides.
The leader of Hamas, the Islamist movement that has controlled the Gaza Strip since 2007, claims to have pushed the Israelis back, even though his group itself suffered heavy casualties.
Despite the deaths of several Hamas leaders and the confinement of the 1.7 million inhabitants of the Gaza Strip in one of the most desolate and densely populated corners of the planet, Israel has so far failed to destroy Hamas.
In fact, Hamas is gaining ground in the West Bank, which is controlled by the rival moderate Palestinian group Fatah.
And the Hamas leaders might conclude that time is on their side.
As Islamists have gained influence in the Arab world, Hamas has been able to attract powerful and wealthy friends to its side.
Turkey, a rising regional power once considered Israel's closest Muslim ally, has sided with Hamas - as has Qatar, one of the richest and most dynamic Gulf states.
Hamas's cheering supporters believe that an Islamist crescent is forming around Israel - from Lebanon in the north, where militant Hezbollah is in power, to Syria, where rebels of an increasingly Islamist character may face the overthrow of Bashar Assad, to Jordan, where Hamas allies are threatening the king.
And in particular, the rise of the Muslim Brotherhood under President Muhammad Morsi in Egypt - by far the most populous and most important Arab country - on the southern flank of Israel has changed the balance of the region for the long term.
Hosni Mubarak, the secularist despot who ruled Egypt for 30 years until his fall in 2011, had little time left for Hamas.
In contrast, the Brotherhood's relationship with Hamas is more muted and its leaders more dependent on popular opinion.
In future diplomatic negotiations, Hamas may prove to be an actor that cannot be ousted even by Israel and the United States.
The Israeli hardliners, on the other hand, draw the opposite conclusion.
Militarily, Hamas is no longer a threat.
The Israeli missile defense system, Iron Dome, has proven itself and many of the Hamas missiles have been destroyed.
At least for a while, Israel will be able to sleep more peacefully.
The United States is firmly on the diplomatic side, and many European countries have blamed Hamas for the latest escalation of violence.
Israel has done well in recent years, especially under Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu, who has largely ignored the peace process.
Although rockets from the Gaza Strip have killed some 30 Israelis since 2004, the country has remained relatively free of suicide bombers, not least thanks to the blockades that have penetrated the West Bank and thus into the main part of a potential Palestinian state, protecting the Jewish settlements, which have been declared illegal under international law but are continuing to expand.
Netanyahu is in a good position, his Likud party having allied itself with an even more militant group under Avigdor Lieberman in the run-up to the elections on 22 January.
Why should we also coddle these treacherous Palestinians and allow them to have their own state?
If they were in control of the West Bank, wouldn't they be firing missiles like their counterparts in Gaza?
No, it's better to keep them behind the wall and punish them if they dare to raise their heads.
The hardliners may be able to prevail, but the Arab Spring could be a blow to them.
Even if the Islamists now in power in Egypt and other countries have little left for Israel, they will focus first on the problems in their own country.
Israel's defence budget is larger than that of its four Arab neighbors combined.
A war with the local superpower will do little to help the new Arab governments to rebuild their economies.
The fact that the pragmatic President Morsi is joining forces with Barack Obama to achieve a ceasefire could be a promising sign - and perhaps symbolize the beginning of a new era.
Israelis should think long term too.
While the rest of the Arab world is taking timid steps towards democratization, Palestinians continue to be deprived of their right to self-determination - a powder keg that will undoubtedly one day explode in the Israeli occupied territories, just as a bus exploded in Tel Aviv this week.
The repression is already undermining democracy in the Jewish state, and as the Arab population grows, this situation will only get worse.
Bloody operations to push back Hamas in the Gaza Strip will increasingly take on diplomatic value over the years.
Both sides need a push from the outside.
The correct answer is the one advocated by the more reasonable representatives of both sides, most of the rest of the world and this newspaper: two states, to which Israel cedes territory for security purposes.
The hope - small for the near future - is that the ceasefire will give outsiders more leverage to enforce this solution.
Egypt must now join Turkey and Qatar in stopping arms supplies to the Gaza Strip and is better positioned than ever to convince Hamas of the idea of a Jewish state based on the 1967 borders, supplemented by territorial exchanges and a shared Jerusalem.
The Arab nations outside the group should also try to bring Hamas and Fatah to an agreement.
This would do more for the creation of a Palestinian state than the forthcoming application for UN observer status.
Obama must also do his part to get Israel to negotiate.
During his first term, he failed to present his own peace plan.
Far away in the White House, it seems he's just as averse to involvement.
But that is a regrettable, short-sighted perspective.
The United States has a vital interest in a stable Middle East.
And that includes a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians.
Australian laws on uniform cigarette packaging come into force
Health warnings and disease-related body parts on neutral green packaging identical for all tobacco brands
The world's first uniform cigarette and tobacco packaging laws have been enacted in Australia, replacing brand logos and colours with neutral olive green covers, which also feature dramatic images of diseased body parts and infants and children affected by cigarette smoke.
Apart from the different health warnings and images, from next Saturday the only difference between the packages is in the brand names, which are printed in identical, small print.
Australia is introducing the strictest regulations on tobacco packaging in the world.
The Australian federal government wants to discourage young people from smoking by eliminating the glamorous image of tobacco use.
The government says that studies have shown that people who have not started smoking by the age of 26 are 99% more likely to stop smoking afterwards.
"You can see from young children that they understand the message that tobacco companies are trying to promote with their brand image", says Minister of Health Tanya Plibersek, citing studies that have shown, for example, that children associate the crown of a logo with the idea of a princess.
Although Australia has one of the lowest smoking rates in the world and the changes will have only a minor impact on the profits of multinational corporations, other countries are already considering similar steps.
The tobacco lobby fought hard against the laws.
It was said that the laws would promote the black market, leading to cheaper and more easily accessible cigarettes.
"The laws will lead to serious unintended consequences", says Scott McIntyre of British American Tobacco Australia.
Chinese and Indonesian counterfeiters will be selling far larger quantities of these products on the streets of Australia.
Others say the laws have boosted their business.
Sandra Ha of Zico Import Pty Ltd, a small family business, notes that demand for cigarette cases and silicone lids to cover the intolerable packaging has skyrocketed since British American Tobacco, Britain's Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco failed to challenge the laws in Australia's highest court two months ago.
Zico has sold up to 6,000 units to wholesale stores and is waiting for new stock.
We're good at this.
