In a world of constant electricity, it's nice to be bored sometimes
This Thanksgiving, I spent five unexpected hours at the airport when our plane crashed due to mechanical problems and we had to wait for another flight.
So I had enough time to get bored with a few thoughts.
I don't want to lie.
Waiting half a day at the airport for a flight is pretty nerve-wracking - even when books, magazines and iPhones (and, of course, tax-free shopping) are available.
But a growing number of academics and child development experts are pointing to boredom as a positive trait.
If it's up to them, it's okay for us - and our kids - to be bored sometimes.
This forces the brain to get lost in interesting thought processes, which may encourage creativity.
And because most of us nowadays stare at one screen or another almost all the time, we no longer enjoy the benefits of boredom.
So should we welcome boredom with open arms?
- I know.
And no, you didn't.
I shall come back to that.
Like many people, I've always assumed that boredom is a relatively recent phenomenon that has evolved with increasing leisure time.
But Peter Toohey, professor of Greek and Roman history at the University of Calgary, Canada, and author of Boredom: A Lively History (Yale University Press, 2011), does not see it that way.
"In fact, boredom has a very long history", he says.
The walls of Pompeii are adorned with a Latin graffiti about boredom dating back to the first century.
And then there's the question of how we actually define boredom.
According to John D. Eastwood, an associate professor of psychology at York University in Ontario, Canada, the problem is that boredom has been defined and discussed in many ways.
After reading the research literature and presenting the idea to a focus group of about 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues concluded that boredom can be defined as the experience of "wanting to do a satisfying activity but not being able to do it".
Boredom differs from apathy in that the person is not busy but wants to be.
Apathy, on the other hand, does not impel one to do anything.
The key experience of boredom, he says, is a "disturbance of the attention process, coupled with a bad mood and a feeling that time is passing slowly".
Boredom can sound almost like depression.
But Professor Eastwood believes that while these two conditions might be related, bored people see the problem in their environment or the world, whereas depressed people see the problem in themselves.
Sometimes we think we're bored, even if we're just having trouble concentrating.
In their study "The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention", published in September in the journal Perspectives on Psychological Science, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues point to an earlier experiment in which participants listened to a tape on which a person read a magazine article.
Some groups heard a loud television program from the next room that had nothing to do with the content; others heard it at a low volume so that it was barely noticeable; while the third group did not hear the sounds at all.
The people who could hardly hear the television reported feeling more boredom than the other two groups - they had trouble concentrating, could not find a reason for it, and attributed their difficulties to boredom.
Attendance disruption can lead to boredom when you try to concentrate on a difficult or exhausting task, says Mark J. Fenske, associate professor of neuroscience at the University of Guelph in Ontario and one of the authors of the study.
On the other hand, when you do a monotonous activity - "such as searching for defective products on a factory treadmill - music can distract and help you not to feel bored".
In fact, he says, we now know that wiggling and crawling, often interpreted as a sign of boredom, can even combat boredom by keeping people more physically alert.
"Studies have shown that children who are allowed to roam around learn more and retain more information than those who are forced to sit still", says Professor Fenske.
We all get bored at some point - my late flight, a loudspeaker, a particularly tiring movie.
But some people get bored more easily than others.
To measure these differences, researchers developed a "boredom scale" in the 1980's.
On the scale, you'll find statements like, "A lot of things I have to do are repetitive and monotonous", and, "I have so many interests that I don't have enough time for everything".
Using such scales, researchers have found that boys are more likely to become bored than girls, says Stephen Vodanovich, a professor of psychology at the University of West Florida - especially in terms of the need for more and a greater variety of external stimuli.
But generally speaking, teenagers are a pretty tense bunch.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of human and community development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted nearly 400 teenagers and their parents seven to eight times a day with a pager.
He found that 32 percent of teenagers were bored in school and doing their homework, while 23 percent reported being bored when they weren't in school.
Yet, only three percent of parents said they were bored.
Professor Larson says today, 21 years later, he doesn't know whether the percentages of boredom have gone up or down.
He was sure, however, that "youth is perceived as particularly boring", mainly because children and teenagers have little influence on their daily routines.
So back to my original question: Is boredom healthy?
Sometimes not, because in extreme cases it leads people to take extreme physical risks and resort to gambling or drugs to alleviate them, studies have shown.
On the other hand, many philosophers and writers are studying the relationship between boredom and creativity, according to Professor Vodanovich, who has been studying the subject for more than two decades.
"When you're bored, your brain is trying to tell you to do something else", says Gary Marcus, a professor of psychology at New York University.
But the brain doesn't always know what's best to do.
When you're bored and you use that energy to play guitar and cook, you're happy.
