"In an environment where we are constantly over-stimulated, it is difficult to get busy once the noise is silenced".
Colorado doesn 't have a clear policy on the new marijuana law .
Nineteen-year-old community college student and football player Anthony Orozco is on trial in southeastern Colorado for a crime that will soon be legal in that state: possession of a few small marijuana sticks and a pipe he used to smoke them.
According to Orozco, he and some friends were driving in Lamar near the Kansas border one September day when they were stopped.
After the police officer found marijuana in the car, Orozco was charged with possession of drugs and drug paraphernalia - felonies punishable by a $100 fine each - and given a court order.
"We are treated like criminals", says Orozco.
But is he one?
In the uncertain weeks following the state's decision to legalize small amounts of marijuana for personal use, the answer to hundreds of minor drug offenses depends less on the law than on the location.
Hundreds of marijuana-related violations are already being dropped here and in the state of Washington, which passed similar measures.
The police authorities will no longer prosecute adults over 21 for possession of small amounts, which will be legally permitted once the new laws come into force in the next few weeks.
But prosecutors in the more conservative counties of Colorado have announced that they will continue to prosecute existing marijuana offenders and are still subpoenaing people.
At the same time, several cities, from the suburbs of Denver to the Western Mountains, are voting to prevent new, state-licensed marijuana stores from opening in their communities.
"This situation is moving so fast that I don't know what's going to happen next", says Daniel J. Oates, police chief in Aurora, east of Denver.
And regulators in Washington state are also scratching their heads.
They are awaiting guidance on setting up a licensing system for the production, manufacture, distribution and sale of the drug - with a deadline of 1 December 2013.
In Washington, Colorado is considered to be ahead of most states in regulating marijuana, first for medical use and then for personal consumption.
"Colorado has a more regulated market, so the state is well suited for guidance", says Brian E. Smith, spokesman for the Washington State Liquor Control Board.
But Smith also admits that no place or system can do more than serve the sense of a rough guide.
"We have no real precedent to follow", he adds.
Washington's law, called I-502, takes effect on December 6, and it also marks the end of a grey area where the state's licensing system does not yet exist, but possession is legalized.
And uncomfortable practical questions need to be clarified during this time - such as how to reconcile the state's requirement of "adequate access" to licensed marijuana with the ban on cannabis shops within 300 metres of schools, parks, playgrounds and childcare facilities.
"Nowhere will it be harder to find a location for a licensed cannabis business than in urban areas, especially in the Seattle metropolitan area", says Ben Livingston, spokesman for the Center for Legal Cannabis, a newly formed research group.
On November 21, Chief Oates sent an email to his Aurora staff stating that the prosecutor would no longer prosecute minor marijuana offenses involving individuals over the age of 21 and that police would not pursue criminal charges for these offenses "as of now".
Chief Oates added that police will continue to enforce city regulations to regulate medical marijuana growers and will continue to prosecute drug dealers.
In Weld County in northern Colorado, District Attorney Ken Buck takes a more extreme view.
After the vote, he said his agency would continue to prosecute marijuana possession cases, mainly to get users to quit.
Currently, 119 people are facing charges for possession of about 50 grams or less of marijuana, although many have been charged with other offenses.
"Our agency has a duty to prosecute offences that were crimes at the time of the offence", Buck said in a statement.
Reactions are mixed even in places like rural Mesa County, where voters rejected the marijuana initiative.
Police in Grand Junction, the largest city in the county, are no longer charging adults for possession of small amounts.
District Attorney Pete Hautzinger supported this decision, but he also decided not to drop all pending possession proceedings.
"I don't think I'm going to waste my time enforcing the law until it changes", he says.
Although 55% of Colorado voters supported the measure, it was clear from the outset that it would not be easy to reconcile personal marijuana use with the complexities of government and the legal system.
And the conflicting reactions across the state fueled a deep division among local officials over the big green experiment.
District attorneys are a "cultural barrier", says Sean McAllister, a Denver lawyer who represents marijuana offenders in court and acts as a spokesman for the National Organization for the Reform of Marijuana Laws.
"They have spent so much of their lives prosecuting people for legalization that they still cannot accept it", he believes.
As the first states to treat small amounts of marijuana like alcohol, Colorado and Washington are being treated as national models for drug legalization.
As advocates and government officials prepare for an era of legal sale, they are also nervously waiting for instructions from the federal government, which wants to continue to treat the sale and cultivation of marijuana at the federal level as a crime.
Supporters of the legalization movement hope the Justice Department will relent.
Despite several sensational arrests of medical marijuana users and sellers, the federal government has permitted the sale of medical marijuana in Colorado, Washington, and 16 other states for the most part.
Kevin A. Sabet, former drug policy adviser to the Obama administration, believes that while law enforcement officials are unlikely to enter doors to seize smaller amounts of drugs, they will likely be reluctant to tolerate the legal, state-regulated marijuana business under the new legislation.
Several cities in Colorado aren't even waiting for the federal government to act.
Even before election day, some local governments approved moratoriums on new marijuana shops, although they may not open for about a year.
Last week, Montrose, a city in the West, passed a six-month ban, which is expected to be passed next week.
"We don't want to be in a position where we're licensing somebody and then we're facing a big problem at the federal level", said City Councilman Bob Nicholson.
Our community voted against this law change.
We're going to be guided by what the community has decided, not what the state has decided.
There are still many unanswered questions.
Petronella Wyatt: I was bullied at Oxford because I'm a Tory
It's not just today's university students who are being attacked for their beliefs.
It had always been my greatest dream to get a place at Oxford University.
Both my father and my older brother had attended what I once considered the world's greatest temple of knowledge, a modern Greek symposium that promoted the great pillars of civilization -- free thought and tolerance.
But within two weeks of moving to Worscester College in the late 1980s - where I had planned to study history - I had packed my bags again, causing the first scandal of my life.
My father broke down in tears.
My friends were confused.
The Evening Standard said I left because I had a problem with fellow students having sex in the next room.
Author A. N. Wilson mischievously explained that I had dropped out of college because I was forced to drink from damaged cups.
The truth was less amusing.
I ran away.
Yes, because I was systematically bullied and threatened.
Not because of my rather unusual name, or because I came from a private school.
I had been harassed for only one reason - a reason that seemed even more narrow and cruel in this supposed cradle of enlightenment: My now-deceased father Woodrow Wyatt had been a key adviser to Margaret Thatcher and I was a supporter of the Conservative Party.
Why am I bringing this up now?
Now, recent reports suggest that a new generation of moderate-right students are suffering similar persecution.
The organized and growing hatred of Tory students in Oxford has now grown to such a degree that a group of them last week called for equal protection for gays, disabled people and ethnic minorities.
Conservative members of the Junior Common Room (JCR) at Corpus Christi College say that because of their political views, they are "often actively isolated, personally attacked, and declared unwelcome".
They are demanding a seat on their college's equality committee to ensure that their opinions can be freely expressed.
Their situation was made worse by a recent BBC Two documentary about political students, "Wonderland: Young, Bright and on the Right", which portrayed the Tories as eccentrics and neo-Nazis.
It showed, among others, graduate Joe Cooke, former president of the conservative Oxford University Students' Union, driving a Rolls-Royce and sporting a silver suit and silver-plated cane.
At other universities, conservative students say they are seen as "scapegoats for the introduction of higher tuition fees".
Luke Black, 20, vice-president of the conservative student union at the University of Nottingham, told a Sunday newspaper: "There is a growing left-wing tendency in universities.
People think we're like the Bullingdon Club without ever meeting".
Samuel Roberts, 21, a history student at Corpus Christi who initiated the petition for greater protection, said such a climate is "uncomfortable". 19-year-old Stephanie Cherill, the designated president of Oxford's conservative student union, said she had observed a growing rejection of moderate-right students among JCR members.
"This is a threat to intellectual discourse and to the well-being of members", she says.
In my first few weeks at Oxford, I was one of those minorities.
I arrived in September 1986 as an incredibly shy 18-year-old.
The hatred of the Conservative Party had reached its peak.
Last year, the university voted to withhold an honorary degree from Margaret Thatcher, a former student, because of cuts in higher education.
The atmosphere would have scared even Stalinists.
In the first few days of the first semester week, when new students meet each other and the tutors, I get a taste of what's to come.
I found that the tutors not only tolerated the ridicule of Tory students, but even took part in it with pleasure.
Political themes such as the miners' strike, privatization and the government's refusal to sanction South Africa's apartheid regime found their way into the wooden board rooms of the tutorial.
The first of these events, I was supposed to translate 18th-century French texts into English, and I was not prepared for what was to come.
"Miss Wyatt", said the tutor Harry Pitt (who has since died), "please translate the first paragraph".
I tripped.
Pitt was a little man with a face like cake dough, and pretty nasty.
"Do Thatcherites refuse to learn French, or are they just stupid?" he asked me.
The other students giggled.
Tears are pouring in my eyes.
"I suggest you take a few French lessons in your spare time - that is, if you are not too busy with your social activities", Pitt grinned.
I returned to my room with my head hanging down.
That night, I was sitting alone at dinner in college when someone gently tapped me on the shoulder.
It was a second-year English student named James, who introduced himself as a member of the conservative student union.
"I know who you are", he said kindly.
Unfortunately, it is what it is.
Anyone suspected of being a Tory is harassed.
It's bad enough for me, but they know your father's close to Margaret Thatcher, so it's gonna be worse for you.
Most Tory freshmen pretend to be Labour.
Later, I tried to pretend at a local pub.
I insisted that I did not agree with Mrs Thatcher on all points.
This trick was to prove unsuccessful.
A freshman in philosophy, politics and economics, who had ironically attended what was considered conservative Eton College, said to me, "You are the daughter of a fascist pig".
You're all dirty.
Other students shared his opinion.
I was perverted and dirty.
"How do Tories have sex?" one asked me.
They're beating each other, aren't they?
I felt as homosexuals must have felt before the more liberal legislation of the United States.
Would I ever be able to live a normal life at Oxford University?
Would I be able to meet like-minded people after dark?
Should I turn to the Labour Party and suppress my natural inclinations?
The three years ahead of me stretched before my mental eye into a purgatory of rejection and isolation.
The only tutor who openly identified himself as a Tory was Norman Stone, a professor of contemporary history who was based at my college.
He was hated not only for being a conservative, but also for advising Thatcher on foreign policy and writing speeches for her.
He was only there a few times.
He hated the place, found it provincial and petty, and rejected it for its Marxist-determinist perspective on history.
In 1997 he accepted a professorship at Bilkent University in Ankara, Turkey.
"You're not going to be happy here", he told me.
I began to commute between Oxford and my parents' house, finding refuge with more receptive friends and family members in the city.
I told my father I hated Oxford and why I did it.
He seemed incredulous.
During his time in the 1940s, all political views were accepted.
"But it's the best place in the world", he said in a low voice.
They would never do that, not in my dream city of towertops.
Even my Communist friends were always well-mannered.
His wet eyes were blurred.
Give it a shot.
I'm sure they're just teasing you.
It would break my heart if you left.
Exhausted by my frequent trips to London, my emotional resistance weakened.
One of my male friends, also a Tory, had succumbed to pressure and renounced his beliefs.
During a tutorial the following week, another history teacher had seriously claimed that I was "an enemy of the people", and I decided to do the same.
Although I was secretly crushed by shame, I admitted that my parents had "brainwashed" me, calling them "old fools".
The relief was short-lived.
It was my father who put the final nail in the coffin of my Oxford career.
At the time, he was writing two columns a week for the Murdoch Press.
My door was locked.
I hid in my room, and after five minutes my stalkers gave up.
When they left, I packed a suitcase and took the first train to London.
I never went back.
You can call me a crying cocksucker.
But no 18-year-old should ever have to suffer such intimidation and malice in an educational institution.
And even more tragic, it was Oxford -- a university that not only produced 14 Tory prime ministers, but still hides behind an undeserved reputation for equality and freedom of thought.
"Valentino prefers elegance to fame"
On the occasion of the exhibition "Valentino - Master of Couture", which opened in London this week, ABC talks to Naty Abascal, Fiona Thyssen-Bornemisza and other famous customers of the Italian fashion maker.
