"I love this palace", he says with his distinctive Italian accent.
This exhibition is the culmination of a story whose sole protagonist is "il signore" Garavani, but which could not have been written without his distinguished clientele.
Valentino had always been fascinated by the stuffy and distant world of the nobility.
The first hall of this exhibition, which will be on view until 3 March, contains a wealth of private letters and photographs signed by the most distinguished aristocrats, from Princess Salimah Aga Khan, to Princess Marie-Chantal of Greece and Margaret of England, to Lord Snowdon.
Valentino presents these personal memories as trophies of his social ascent from a modest fashion designer in the northern Italian city of Voghera to an international jet-set idol.
Being in love with a noble doesn't have to be a disadvantage.
"At least they don't show their curls on your beautiful carpet, as some beautiful pop stars do", says Baroness Fiona Thyssen-Bornemisza.
In the 1960's and 1970's, the two lived in the Alps and were good friends.
Valentino is a spectacular, generous and elegant host.
"We were all delighted to be invited to his house in Gstaad", explains the ex-wife of "Heini" Thyssen, close friends with forgotten beauties such as Marella Agnelli or Eugenie Niarchos.
Valentino has always preferred the elegance of fame.
And yet he is a star.
Valeria Mazza, in a dress by Valentino
