The world's most difficult job: the human working animals of Kawah Ijen
For four euros, the holders of the Indonesian volcano risk their lives and health to carry 70 kilos of sulfur over the steep, rocky paths.
There are people for whom their work is hell, and others literally work in hell.
This is the case of Anto Wijaya, one of 400 miners who earn their living by extracting sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano on the eastern island of Java, Indonesia.
To do this, he must descend daily to the bottom of his crater, where the sulfur-containing gas that flows from the earth solidifies in contact with the air.
After breaking out large sulphur stones, which can weigh up to 70 kilograms in total, he carries them on his shoulders in two bamboo baskets over the steep stone paths.
Although it is only 250 meters [250 feet] to the top of the volcano, which rises to an altitude of 2,386 meters [2,386 feet], the exhausted riders take more than 40 minutes to climb at turtle speed, keeping their balance and taking care not to slip and fall.
They know that every step can cost them their lives, as happened to a French tourist who fell off the steep slopes of Kawah Ijen years ago.
The miners of Kawah Ijen earn 5 euro cents for every kilo of sulphur they mine.
Once they reach the top, they make their way between the tourists who photograph them like circus monkeys and run three kilometers in the tiringly heavy baskets to the scales set up by a mining company a little further down at an altitude of 1,850 meters
The company is PT Candi Ngrimbi, which has been exploiting the volcano's resources and (never better) its workers since 1960, paying them 662 Indonesian rupees (5 euro cents) for every kilo of sulphur.
They then sell it to the petrochemical industry for 10,000 rupees (83 cents) each, because this mineral is widely used in everyday life and is used to make matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite, and even to bleach sugar.
"Since we normally carry 70 kilograms, we get about 46,000 rupees ($1,200) for each trip", explains Anto, who normally makes three trips a day.
He takes three hours to complete each course, and by the end of the day he has 138,000 rupees.
What may seem like a miserable wage for such an inhuman effort is three times what he would earn in the field.
"The daily wage of the miners here, where the coffee harvest is 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) a day and the average monthly income is two million rupees (167 euros), is very high", explains the porter, who previously worked as a mason on the tourist island of Bali.
There he earned 75,000 rupees a day, and the work was not so hard, but Anto returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a nearby village, for a reason that is as important in Indonesia as sulfur: "I married a girl from Bali, where they are Hindus, and I brought her to Java to convert her to Islam".
Anto has asthma, breathing difficulties, frequent coughing, and irritation of the eyes due to the toxic gases.
The 27-year-old Anto has been risking his life for three years at Kawah Ijen, where sulfur has already left its first traces, even though he covers his face with a mask and special glasses.
Anto has asthma, breathing difficulties, frequent coughing, and irritation of the eyes due to the toxic gases from the volcano.
This is the price he must pay for achieving his dream.
"I'm going to work here for two more years because I want to open a shop or learn Spanish or French", he promises in more than plain English.
This charming and intelligent but life-threatening young man could be a tour guide, a waiter, or a hotel receptionist, but instead he is doing the work of a doorman.
He shares a dirty wooden hut with other carriers and gets up at two o'clock every morning because the sulfur flows out at night, where its distinctive yellow color shines blue in the dark.
Defying the shadows, he climbs into the crater in the light of a small headlamp on his helmet, which he bought with his own money.
About 400 carriers load the baskets of sulfur on their shoulders at the crater floor.
Despite its large profits, the mining company has not mechanised sulphur mining to save costs and does not supply any equipment to carriers who work on their own account and are paid by weight.
They also do not receive a share of the 30,000 rupees ($2.80) per camera that the park's rangers charge tourists for photographing the volcano and the human body, along with the 15,000 rupees ($1.80) entrance fee.
"This work is for the animals, not for the people", protested Madrusin, a 42-year-old hard-working porter who has been working at Kawah Ijen for three decades since leaving school.
He is able to carry up to 110 kg and assures that he will continue "as long as he can", because he needs the money to raise his three children between the ages of 10 and 18.
I'm not retiring, I'm dying here because the volcano was my whole life.
Even when the sulfur burns your throat and itches your eyes, when the wind suddenly turns and the miners get caught in the thick pillars that rise from the crater, the men are so tough that no one complains of serious illnesses... except, of course, the usual breathing problems, arthrosis, pain in the knees and blisters on the shoulders that have deformed from the weight of the baskets.
With the basket on his back, Unainik, at 53, is only able to carry 50 kg.
Each day, he and his companions break 15 tons of sulfur from the volcano, which is transported by three trucks along a goat path through the bushes to a camp in Tamansari, 18 kilometers away.
"I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano was my whole life", Unainik explains, opening his mouth wide, missing some teeth.
The oldest of his five children, at 30, also works as a sulphur carrier.
Time passes, but poverty persists generation after generation in one of the hardest jobs in the world: that of those who work as human donkeys at the Kawah Ijen.
Singapore needs babies to save the economy
Singaporeans blame their lack of children on their careers, stress, and the cost of real estate and child rearing.
"The population of Singapore must grow".
I am a patriotic husband, you are my patriotic wife: let us fulfill our civic duty and create life!
It seems unbelievable that the verses are part of a mint candy commercial, but nevertheless - or just because of that - they went viral on YouTube in Singapore earlier this year.
