We knew that the government had tried many things, such as marketing perfume with pheromones or organizing speed-dating evenings.
Many of these ideas may have been creative, but they didn't necessarily lead to success.
So we thought, why don't we do something as creative as possible to address this problem, like, say, compose a rap song?
1.2 Children
The one who does not take this issue lightly is the government of Singapore.
Every year, it spends $1,300 on policy measures to encourage citizens to have more children.
A government package for couples and parents provides up to $15,000 per child, extends maternity leave and distributes tax breaks.
But everything has been a little bit of a success.
Singapore is a rich, high-tech city-state in Southeast Asia, also known for the conservatism of its rulers and its strict social controls.
According to its national population office, the birth rate is currently 1.2 children per woman.
The last time this rate was above 2 - also known as the replacement rate - was in 1976.
So why aren't Singaporeans having more children?
Tan Wei Ming, director of marriage and family policy at the National Population Agency, says that this is due to "better education" and "greater career opportunities".
"This has allowed people to have much more options in terms of goals and priorities than just getting married and starting a family", she explains.
These changes in social conditions have contributed to the increase in the number of single people and to the delay in marriage and births, resulting in a decrease in the birth rate in Singapore.
Meanwhile, an immigration policy aimed at drastically increasing immigration to counteract population decline has led to resentment among the local population.
In Singapore, there are websites where the little-disguised xenophobia against many new immigrants is flourishing, especially against the Chinese, who are criticized for keeping wages low and not integrating.
The rise in immigration is also seen as one of the reasons why Singapore's ruling party scored its worst election result since independence last year.
Since the elections, an attempt has been made to correct the problem with higher contributions and taxes for foreign workers.
Unanticipated Consequences
While the falling birth rate has the known effects on a nation's economic growth, tax revenues, health care costs and immigration policy, the example of Singapore also shows unexpected consequences.
The government is trying to get so many small apartments built.
It is already having an impact on the housing market.
The Urban Development Authority has begun to control the number of small apartments, known as "shoe boxes", that are allowed to be built in certain areas of the city.
These apartments have a living area of 46 square metres and show a great sales success.
However, there is concern that they may promote the single-person lifestyle and discourage construction companies from building large family homes.
But Lim Yew Soon, CEO of real estate firm EL Developers, says his "shoe boxes" sell much faster than larger residential units.
They're so popular, and the units sell out days and even weeks faster than the larger units.
This makes them much better for our cash flow.
However, he admits that the new standards give clearer guidance to developers who have previously faced obstacles in building too many small housing units within a project.
Too much stress
Singapore is a city-state.
Even if these new rules could pave the way for a rise in the national birth rate, it is clear from discussions with Singaporeans working in the financial sector that they will not have much of an impact.
"People are under a lot of stress, and housing and education are expensive, so many people are putting it off", says one young manager.
The kids can get others.
"It is important for me to have my own money and time", says another man in his early 20's.
Men and women cite their careers, stress, and the cost of property and education as reasons why they cannot have children.
That's why Singaporeans have the final say when it comes to having children - there's so much the government can do.
