I signed up for Twitter to express myself and write interesting tweets.
"I don't know if anyone is answering me, I'm just uploading them", he adds.
"Social networks are fun, I can talk quickly with distant relatives or friends", he says.
When asked, he replies that he would never accept an invitation from a stranger.
Even if someone recommended a stranger, he would ignore it.
The case of 14-year-old José is different.
The teenager has user accounts on Hotmail, Facebook, My Space and Ask, and in Ask he admits not to know 20 of the people he added to his friend list.
"I'm not afraid of that because we have something in common, for example, music", he says.
According to the boy, no one gave him any clues or asked him for his address or phone number.
"If someone is bullying me or asking me to do it, I just remove them from my account", he admits.
José joined Ask after reading a recommendation on Twitter.
The boy is not unaware of what is now known as cyberbullying.
A friend's acquaintance was blackmailed on a social network.
They threatened him and demanded money.
"He never knew who it was", he assures.
According to José, the victim didn't close the user account.
"He just did it in private".
It then explains a series of steps to configure a user account securely.
Unlike Jorge, this young man would upload photos of acquaintances in uncomfortable or embarrassing situations.
Yeah, I would if I didn't like him or if I wanted to fuck him.
"But I know this is cyberbullying", he explains.
The key issues
Marielos Porras, an English teacher with a degree in education and learning, believes that to orient children and young people, it must be understood that the purpose of social networks is to inform.
"The Internet was originally a search engine, but with the advent of these sites, the rules of the game have changed", she says.
Porras explains that academic Marc Prensky, who holds a master's degree in education from Yale University and is the author of "Digital Natives and Immigrants", coined these terms to explain the phenomenon.
The digital natives are them, the children and teenagers who grew up with this technology.
"We are the digital immigrants who are supposed to teach them, when we are still learning ourselves", he says.
He explains that this is a complex issue "because we require them to have a defined criterion for what can be disseminated, published or said, and this at an age when maturity is not sufficient".
"They should also be selective when it is most important to them to be popular, to have thousands of friends, without thinking about the consequences", he adds.
According to the expert, the most effective way to teach children and teenagers about privacy is to ask them questions that make them think.
"Telling them not to do it doesn't work", he says.
Porras goes on to mention a few possibilities: There are things you wouldn't tell a stranger, so why do it on the Internet?
Or, would you like to have a photo of you posted, like the one you posted about a friend?
You know what other people are posting about you?
Did you ask the other people for permission before you tagged photos of parties?
And one more question, do you need everyone to know what you're doing at all times?
Another point is to make them understand that they have to act online as they do offline.
It's the same rules.
"Someone outside the Internet is acting with respect, morality and other principles, and the same must apply to social networks", he explains.
The Commission
Estuardo Guardia, a university professor, elementary school teacher, and educational consultant, comments that it is essential that parents carefully read the guidelines of social networks.
If they understand all the sections, they have a solid foundation to talk to their children about the importance of opening an online user account.
"For example, age, or what you can share or publish", he explains.
Guardia says the children need to be reminded of the lesson "You must not talk to strangers".
The UNASUR summit concluded without the publication of the Lima Declaration
The 6th Summit of Presidents of the Union of South American Nations (UNASUR) ended today in Peru without the publication of the Lima Declaration, which had been announced beforehand and was supposed to be signed by the seven present governments.
The document was signed by the President of the Republic of Peru, who was the head of the UNASUR, and was sent to the UNSC in December of that year.
When asked about the text, they said that the content was presented to the press by the President of Peru, Ollanta Humala, in brief statements.
Press access to information about the summit was limited at all times.
During the day, the press room only broadcasted the picture of the presidential meeting without sound with the message "private session, limited audio".
The few pieces of information circulated among journalists were obtained by the press officers of some of the Unasur governments present at the meeting, but not by the Peruvian press officer.
The only document that was circulated during the day was the list of participating presidents, which caused discomfort among the hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who demanded more information.
Afterwards, the Peruvian presidency sent the media an email with the summit's "concluding statement", but it was the Humala statement and not the official summit closing document.
Last October, Peru hosted the Third Summit of South American and Arab States (ASPA), and on this occasion, despite press pressures, the so-called Lima Declaration, which had been announced earlier, was not published either.
The official website of the ASPA confirms that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities emphasized that the information systems for journalists were in place, but they severely restricted access to information.
The summit also ended with Chile and Peru jointly committing themselves to accepting a judgment of the Court of Justice of The Hague settling a border dispute between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met during the regional meeting and confirmed that they would accept the decision of the International Court of Justice, which begins in The Hague on Monday, to hear the pleas of both sides in the trial initiated by Lima against Santiago.
"We will follow and implement the judgment on the differences that we are currently presenting to this International Court of Justice", Humala said, along with his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile was, is and will continue to be a country that respects international law, seeks peaceful solutions to disputes, concludes agreements and submits to international courts", added Piñera, saluting Humala with a handshake before the flags of both countries.
The two presidents' confirmation that they would submit to the ICC came after Colombia, following a decision on the maritime borders with Nicaragua which it considered a grave error, had brought an action against the Bogotá Convention, in which it agreed to submit to the judgments of this International Court of Justice.
The summit was attended by the Presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff, Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, which has been excluded from UNASUR since 2011 following the ouster of its President Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
The host, President Ollanta Humala, opened the talks in the morning and closed the summit shortly after noon in Lima.
The Head of State read the final document, in which he announced that 16 decisions had been taken and the lines of action for 31 projects between the South American countries had been established, with a total investment amount of 17 billion dollars.
He said that the UNASUR countries "will take significant steps towards the goal of South American citizenship, to which we extend the Residence Rights Decisions".
He announced that measures would be taken to "improve cooperation in the fight against urban insecurity and organised transnational crime, and measures to improve access to medicines and the Internet at low prices in all areas of South America, and to act jointly and efficiently in the event of natural disasters".
With the crisis in Europe, "economic consolidation (in Latin America) must not be a triumph, but rather serve to expand our productive capacity and to show our peoples a better future", Humala added.
"We have decided to give priority to a series of 31 emblematic projects that are designed to improve spatial connections in South America, especially in rural and border areas... and thus unite our countries and open up new economic forms", the Peruvian president said in a statement read.
The Commission has also been asked to submit a proposal for a regulation on the protection of the environment in the Community.
The final document also referred to the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in this country will serve to re-establish it in the Union of South American Nations", from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to continue to be an integrated region of prosperity and peace and good neighbourly relations was another aspect emphasised at the Summit.
In this context, Colombian President Juan Manuel Santos said before attending the regional meeting that he expected to meet his Nicaraguan counterpart, Daniel Ortega, in Mexico on Saturday to respectfully address the maritime conflict following a ruling by the International Court of Justice challenged by Bogotá.
"I may meet with President Daniel Ortega tomorrow (Saturday)", Santos said.
"We will review all these options - they are not exclusive, and the agreement with Nicaragua also makes talks with Nicaragua necessary", he stressed.
"I hope to be able to tell President Ortega that we will treat this matter as civilized and respectful as possible", Santos added.
Santos and Ortega are scheduled to meet in Mexico on Saturday, where they intend to attend the inauguration of the new president of that country, Enrique Peña Nieto.
As part of the summit, the bloc's defence ministers also met in advance to adopt the 2013 action plan, which aims to strengthen dialogue and consensus on the defence of the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay are members of UNASUR, although the latter is currently excluded.
Peru holds the provisional presidency of the regional bloc.
'South America must learn from the integration of its citizens', says Rafael Correa
The President of Ecuador, Rafael Correa, today confirmed that the creation of a common citizenship is a goal, with "South America actually having something to learn from Europe".
Correa, who attended the 6th Summit of Presidents of the Union of South American Nations (UNASUR) held in Lima, told Peru's state television that Europeans "killed each other in World War II and other conflicts" and "today are practically a fatherland".
In this sense, he defended the project of creating a South American citizenship, which the member states of Unasur are pushing forward.
'We must achieve free movement of citizens and workers in all South American countries, as is already the case in the Andean Community; however, there are still reactionary sectors that seek a return to the past,' he warned.
The President of Ecuador also supported the restructuring of the Organization of American States (OAS) with the aim of reducing the influence of the Anglo-Saxon states and taking into account those which signed the San José Convention on Human Rights.
Those who teach never commit to anything, and in return we South Americans always sign everything.
"It is incomprehensible that the Inter-American Commission on Human Rights is based in Washington and is funded by the United States", he said, referring to the political asylum granted by Ecuador to WikiLeaks founder Julian Assange.
Correa assured that he did not regret this decision, because he did not betray his principles, but he followed his "deep democratic values and views on human rights".
He added that at the time, there were "reasonable suspicions that Assange was being extradited to a third country and that his proceedings would not be adhered to".
He also criticised the Swedish judiciary, which had asked him to interrogate him on his own territory for an alleged sexual offence, while 'Swedish jurisprudence allows this to be done via videoconference, which could have been conducted via the Ecuadorian embassy in London'.
Correa stated that there was a risk that Assange's health and mental state would be affected.
"I have not spoken to him since he is in our embassy, but the ambassador informed me that he has a slight lung problem, but not serious", the Ecuadorian head of state said.
However, there is a risk of physical and psychological harm because of being trapped in a confined space and not being able to exercise outdoors.
"It would affect the health of every person", he added.
Correa said that the solution to the asylum granted to Assange since June at the Ecuadorian embassy in London is to grant him a waiver allowing him to travel to Ecuador, and that this is in the hands of Britain, Sweden and the legal authorities of Europe.
We are not dealing with human rights, we do not use that word in this case, but there have been constant discussions.
"The solution to this problem is in the hands of the UK, Sweden and the legal authorities of Europe because Assange's lawyer, Baltazar Garzón, is conducting a series of proceedings in various European bodies", he explained.
And "If Britain gives this waiver tomorrow, I think this is done".
And if Sweden were to question Mr Assange at the Ecuadorian embassy in London or via Skype, as is permitted by Swedish case law and has been done in other cases, the problem would be solved.
Correa took the opportunity to assert himself as a defender of press freedom, saying that what he does not tolerate is "the mediocrity, the malice and the lies that undermine free speech".
"The greatest enemies of press freedom are not the bad and perverse politicians, but bad journalists who seek profit and blackmail", he said.
In this sense, he congratulated himself that Ecuador is no longer ruled by such journalists "nor by the bankers or the hegemonic and bourgeois countries", and anticipated that in a re-election "the revolution will be deepened to continue the path in this right direction".
Correa also supported the decision to maintain the veto against Paraguay in the Unasur at least until its next elections, arguing that the body "must remain tough and not accept opportunism and no coup dressed as legal" because it "has destroyed the legitimacy of democracy in Paraguay".
The President of Ecuador also considered the desire of his Colombian counterpart, Juan Manuel Santos, now and after the ruling of the International Court of Justice in The Hague, which favoured the maritime sovereignty of Nicaragua, to negotiate with Nicaragua the maritime boundaries between the two countries as "absolutely justified".
At present, this judgment is not being implemented.
It is a problem between a South American and a Central American state.
Conflict is inevitable, but it must be overcome in the pursuit of a common path.
They need to be dealt with comprehensively so that we can overcome them and look forward.
He also expressed confidence in the successful resolution of the disputes over the maritime borders between Peru and Chile before the same court, and said that "it is right for Latin America to appeal to international bodies if both countries commit to accept the verdict, even if it is very hard".
Regarding the possibility of running for the next presidential election in Ecuador to complete his third consecutive term, he said that he sees this possibility "with great optimism and joy, although sometimes it is very difficult".
Correa assured that if he lost the February 2013 elections, he would retire from politics.
I have never been interested in power, but in such unjust circumstances as in Ecuador, this socioeconomic poverty can only be corrected by political power.
"My political movement believed that I was the one who guaranteed this probable victory, so I have to fulfill this responsibility", he said.
If I win, it would be my last term as president, and then I'm retiring from public life.
This is also true if we lose.
"That's settled", he explained.
Correa also referred to the treatment of the health problems of the President of Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, in Cuba.
I just spoke to the Vice President of Venezuela, Nicolás Maduro, and he told me that he had traveled there for a scheduled routine treatment and that he was expected to be able to travel back to Cuba after the election campaign.
"It does not mean that President Chávez's health is in any way deteriorating", he commented.
The Ecuadorian President attended the 6th Summit of Heads of State or Government of the Union of South American Nations (UNASUR) in Lima today, which ended with a call for greater regional integration to ensure sustainable progress, equality and security.
The cause of AIDS deaths is now too late to be recognized
Fabrizio was 21 years old when he tested positive for HIV.
"It was like a bomb went off", he says of the moment he received the diagnosis, which the doctor "tried to defuse without noticeable success".
He hid it from his family.
He decided to take care of his illness on his own and began to learn about it, and he did so with such dedication that he was just celebrating his 43rd birthday.
He is undoubtedly one of the oldest patients in the HIV unit of the Hospital Civil de Guadalajara (HCG), where he came in 1994 after several struggles.
Fabrizio has been living with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) for 22 years, which was hard to imagine in the early 1990's when there were many doubts, few treatment options, and more stigma.
At the time, even the director of one IMSS clinic avoided saying goodbye "because it was a dead end".
AIDS was synonymous with death back then.
Today, it is possible to survive this syndrome with quality of life.
However, many people still come to the hospital unaware of their illness, and the virus has already damaged and exhausted their immune system, and they are victims of opportunistic infections.
31 years after the world's first reported cases of AIDS, "the great success today means that the survival of a patient who starts treatment on time is exactly the same as the survival of the general population", explained Jaime Andrade Villanueva, head of the HIV unit at HCG, saying that this information was backed up by a respected scientific publication in April of this year.
Infectious disease and HIV/AIDS specialist Andrade Villanueva commented that since 2008, scientists have concluded that although AIDS is not a death sentence, years of survival and quality of life depend on the degree of immune system impairment of individuals at the start of treatment and that those who are not drug dependent have a higher chance of surviving: up to 30 years for a count of 200 CD4 and 50 years for a count of 500 CD4.
Simply put, the above suggests that a person diagnosed as HIV-positive at age 25 "can live to be 75 years old without any problems, as long as it is under control", the expert explained.
To properly classify this progress, it must be remembered that the average life expectancy of Mexicans today is 76 years.
Even if mortality has decreased significantly in recent years (in Mexico, the number of people dying from AIDS has decreased from 6,678 cases in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (the annual report of ONUSIDA), it is still true that since the emergence of AIDS, 60 percent of the patients recorded in the national database have died.
In Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011, and as of May this year, 187 have died, but it is assured that since 2005 there has been universal access to antiretroviral medicines.
- So why are people still dying?
- In my opinion, the problem is not access to treatment.
This is my opinion, and this is the way it is in our hospital.
At least for the last 12 years, we haven't had any problems with the supply of medicines, and the problem is that people come in very advanced states because they don't know their infection status, which is very late in the disease.
He makes a striking statement: "Nine out of ten patients come to us when they already have a co-infection, and to affect global mortality, we need earlier diagnosis, and so we need to offer massive screening to all those who need it".
This suggestion is supported by the experts and officials of the Consejo Estatal de Prevención del Sida en Jalisco (Coesida) (Council of State for the Prevention of AIDS in Jalisco) and also by patients like Fabrizio, who had his test done in a private laboratory, for the sole reason that it was done by a friend of his who, despite his young age, was already in the AIDS phase and even had Kaposi's sarcoma (a cancerous tumor), which is one of the usual complications.
Everything is different when you know you have AIDS.
Some think they're going to die, and they don't want to hear anything.
"If I have to die, I'd rather blow up three times", they say in my case.
The change was to improve, I eat well, exercise and take the medication.
Today, all his parents know is that he had cancer.
I live a normal life, just like everybody else.
"I work, I do a lot of things, I have an active but responsible sex life, I take care of my health and that of the other person", says Fabrizio, who agreed to share his intimate details with MILENIO JALISCO to encourage those who are afraid with his testimony today in the context of World AIDS Day.
If they're at risk, they should get tested, and the sooner they know they're HIV positive, the better, and if they know the diagnosis, they should learn how to live responsibly like everyone else.
His message is a summary of the fight against AIDS in 2012.
Condoms behind the counter
There are huge gaps between health programs and the average citizen, explains Ricardo Salazar, a journalist from Guadalajara who has taken up the HIV issue.
And the most important thing is prevention.
In the designated places, "the distribution of condoms has actually increased; they used to be delivered individually, now they give us packages of a hundred, which is good, but there are still people who don't have access to a condom", he said.
Young people are at risk for new infections.
"What do you need them for?" is a common question of ridicule from social workers, school guidance workers, pharmacy and health care workers who don't want young people to be exposed, the correspondent assured.
He suggested that this inefficient distribution be redirected, with condoms not just behind the counter but in delivery machines in public toilets in facilities frequented by young people.
It is not intended to promote promiscuity.
They are not to be paid for beer and motels, as Governor Emilio González said when asked if condoms would be distributed under his administration.
"Sexuality is not like that; the best way is to bring condoms closer to those who are already engaged in sexual activity", he said.
Key data from Jalisco
There are 13,435 cumulative cases (12,158 AIDS and 1,317 HIV).
The state ranks fourth nationally in new and cumulative AIDS cases, and 13th in HIV.
92% of infections are from sexual contact, 6% from blood and 2% from perinatal transmission.
It is estimated that 50,000 people are living with HIV, because for every recorded case, there are four or five people who don't know.
The United States Court of Appeals upheld a judgment that did not recognise the restructuring of the Vitro Group's liabilities, which was achieved through a commercial tender in Mexico, setting an ominous precedent for any national company with branches in a neighbouring country that is in payment difficulties.
So one could say that the procedures for the survival of companies that Mexican law allows are not valid in the land of the stars and stripes, contrary to international agreements.
In practice, the recognition of the ruling by Judge Harlin Hale in the Bancarrotas Court for the Northern District of Texas on June 15 leaves Mexican companies helpless in the face of the confiscation of their property across the Bravo River.
However, the decision opens the door for Mexico's largest glass manufacturer to appeal to the Supreme Court of the United States on three grounds of inconsistency.
While the judge in the case points out that the creditors must be subject to United States bankruptcy law, the New Orleans-based Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit says first that the main case is the commercial bankruptcy case in Mexico.
The first point would mean that international cooperation in insolvency proceedings of undertakings with a cross-border profile is not known.
In fact, the United Nations Model Law for the Unification of International Commercial Law was created for this purpose, with the American Law Institute as the mediator.
Second, the judgment states that without the votes of the companies after the recognition of the liabilities in the bankruptcy estate that the Vitro subsidiaries had with their parent company, the majority required for the restructuring of the liabilities would not have been achieved.
However, this possibility is recognized by Mexican law.
In fact, Vitro is not the first case where this scheme has been authorised.
There are half a dozen examples, including Agremex and Comercial Mexicana, whose liabilities among companies in the group have been confirmed by the Instituto Federal de Concursos Mercantiles (Federal Institute for Commercial Competitions).
It is also true that after the votes of the branches had been deducted, the creditors of Vitro, the creditors who brought actions against Vitro before the courts of the United States, i.e. the vulture funds such as Aurelios Capital, Aurelios Convergencia, Elliot Internacional and Liverpool Limited, would not have reached a majority.
The vote would have been 45 percent to 37 percent.
This is not taken into account by the Court of Appeal.
On the other hand, Vitro is to blame for its difficult situation from 2008 onwards in the context of the great economic crisis in the United States, which hit the country hard.
The González Sada family therefore objects to the same Court of Appeal, so that the vote is taken in plenary, i.e. by all the judges, because only three of them voted.
If this is not granted, the Cerciorare appeal is filed, requesting review of the proceedings by a higher court, in this case the Supreme Court of the United States.
The crux of the case is that the Court set aside a document sent by the Government of Mexico under the name of Figura amicus curiae (Friend of the Court) describing the proceedings conducted by Vitro under the Commercial Competition Act and pointing out that it had strictly adhered to the agreements signed by both countries in order to comply with Chapter 15 of the United States Bankruptcy Code.
It is also noted that the country has complied with the principles of the United Nations Commission on International Trade, i.e. the established rules for cross-border insolvency cases which guarantee equality between debtors and creditors.
Two-sided caramboles: a blow to Vitro and the country.
General account
