As you know, we're talking about a huge sales and distribution center in Mexico, Central America and the Caribbean with products from the country beyond the wall, supplemented by a residential area for the employees of 150 companies.
In the run-up to this, the Canacintra (the national chamber of manufacturing industry) succeeded in uniting the governors of the south-east to oppose the monumental structure which destroyed some protected areas and is the mother of all threats to industry.
ACTA is dead.
Because the government failed to comply with a request from the Senate to explain the conditions and circumstances under which the Mexican Ambassador to Japan signed the Anti-Counterfeiting Trade Agreement, known by its English abbreviation ACTA, the matter has already been filed according to the Mexican Institute of Intellectual Property.
As you know, these measures were taken despite the fact that the Senate had disregarded the possibility because it considered them to be a violation of free expression on social networks.
Homex in the long term
In an effort to pay long-term liabilities without compromising short-term liabilities, the construction company Homex is putting over 500 million pesos of stock certificates on the market.
The issue is the first of four identical issues that promise an interest payment every 28 days.
