Hector "Hetin" Reyes: "Basketball was my life"
The world's most famous basketball player, Héctor "Hetin" Reyes, has been involved in the sport for more than 60 years and has traveled the world.
Few Puerto Ricans have such a large intellectual collection of the country's basketball history as Héctor "Hetin" Reyes.
Before being confined to a wheelchair by a stroke in 2008, Rexes spent 6 years in this sport, whether as a lower-class player, first-team player, commissioner and manager in the BSN with the Vaqueros de Bayamón or president of the Basketball Association.
"I've worn many hats in basketball throughout my life, even several at the same time, when I was president of the BSN, general manager of the national team and president of the federation in the 1990s", Reyes recalled during a visit by Primera Hora to his home in Bayamón, where he lives with Isabel, his faithful wife of more than 50 years.
"Basketball was my life".
Reyes is not exaggerating.
The walls of his house are almost all decorated with photographs and memories of his long career, testifying to them.
Bayamón in the heart
The most emotional memories are those that recall his time with the Vaqueros from the mid-1950s as a player until 1982, when he celebrated his 15th anniversary as co-manager or general manager of the club.
"These were my best years, the ones I enjoyed the most, because I've been a part of eight Vaqueros championships since 1967, whether as a manager, co-manager or a coach.
It was a lot of fulfilling years, including five consecutive championships from 1971 to 1975.
And then I bid farewell to a championship in 1981, the year Jerome Mincy debuted on BSN.
"The first thing I did was to get a job, and then Cuco took over from Ortiz, who was a very good manager", says Reyes.
I remember Gene Bartow, who was a coach here, and he was employed at the University of Alabama, Birmingham, and he said, "I have a very strong, six-foot-tall player.
Do you want it?"
And that was the beginning of Mincy, one of the best players Puerto Rico ever had.
Bartow then recommended free throw specialist Raymond Gausse, who had become a citizen and was one of our best pitchers.
I remember him saying that if Mincy had made Bayamon a champion, Gausse would make another.
The Vaqueros with Gausse championship was granted to him, but from a distance, because he was already at the top of the association in 1988.
At the time, he preferred to enjoy his and Mincy's finishes on the national team.
I remember when we first won the pre-Olympic tournament in Mexico against the United States.
Then came the 1990 World Cup, where we finished fourth, which should have been bronze, if it hadn't been for this Canadian referee, who made us repeat the last play for the second time", Reyes said.
Was that group at the 1990 World Cup the best national team you've ever seen?
She's one of the best, like the one that won the 2004 Olympics against the Dream Team.
But my favorite is the team at the 1991 Pan American Games in Cuba, where we won gold and gave the U.S. team a fight, like when they won bronze against us at the World Cup.
In that team, not only Mincy, Gausse, Ramon Rivas, Fico López and "Piculín" (Ortiz) were back, but also the young players (Javier) "Toñito" Colón and James Carter, the brothers León (Francisco and Edgar) and Mario "Quijote" Morales, who could not be in 1990 due to a knee injury.
One team that may not have been the best in terms of personality but with which we won a gold medal and which brought us great joy was the 1995 pre-Olympic tournament in Neuquén, Argentina.
With players like "Canito" Nieves, Pablo Alicea and young Rolando Hourruitiner as substitutes for the players suspended because of the events at the Pan American Games in Mar del Plata, we won the gold medal against all odds.
Who was the best player in Puerto Rico?
That was Piculin Ortiz, no doubt.
His numbers at the international level are impressive.
No one in Puerto Rico has dominated this level as much as Piculin.
And that's without taking into account his career in the different leagues he's played in.
Who was the best coach from Puerto Rico?
That's a difficult question.
We had a number of good coaches like Julio Toro, Flor Meléndez, Carlos Morales, Raymond Dalmau, Armandito Torres. They were the best coaches in the world.
I like the work of Leo Arill.
What do you think is the best thing you've accomplished in the League?
I was part of the most successful era of the national team from 1988 to 1995, which saw the BSN expand to 17 teams in a season in the early 1990s.
What else do you have to do?
There are things I would have introduced, such as the regionalisation of the lower categories.
That the boys in Ponce, for example, only play in their area and don't meet teams from other corners of the island until the national playoffs.
Today, children make unnecessary trips and play.
At least I can see the results of the required training and training for coaches, officials and referees.
I'm proud of that.
What are you doing today?
I like to listen to music, watch music videos of my time on YouTube, enjoy my grandchildren, and occasionally go to a basketball game.
And of course, I enjoy the company of my wife, Isabel, who has always been by my side.
